<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Irish PM Haughey Apologizes at Tribunal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Former Irish Prime Minister Charles
Haughey apologized at a Dublin tribunal today for misleading an
official tribunal over the case of Haughey receiving a large sum
of cash from an Irish tycoon.
</P>
<P>
Haughey, who had been Irish prime minister between 1979 and
1992, told the tribunal that he was sorry for previously denying,
through his lawyers, that he had received 1.3 million Irish pounds
(about 2 million U.S. dollars) from Irish businessman Benn Dunne
between 1989 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
Explaining why he had earlier denied the allegations,
71-year-old Haughey said that his financial affairs had been
handled by his former partner Des Traynor in an accountancy firm.
</P>
<P>
Haughey noted that Traynor, who was "widely regarded as a
financial expert of exceptional ability," had complete control of
his money since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"He saw it as his personal responsibility to ensure that I
would be free to devote my time and ability to public life and
that I would not be distracted from my political work by financial
concerns."
</P>
<P>
"Traynor had total discretion to act on my behalf without
reference to me. In hindsight, it is clear that I should have
involved myself to a greater degree in this regard," Haughey said.
</P>
<P>
The once most powerful Irish leader made a statement last week
through his legal team, admitting for the first time that he was
recipient of the cash.
</P>
<P>
Dunne, who had earler admitted that he gave Haughey the money
in the form of three bank drafts of about 70,000 pounds (about
112,000 dollars), repeatedly stressed that he never expected "any
favor or benefit" from the former Irish leader. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
