<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Leader Arrives in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak arrived here today to start a visit to Egypt,
his first in this new capacity, the Egyptian Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa welcomed him at the
airport. In a statement upon arrival, Barak expressed appreciation
of Egypt's "pioneering and effective" role in the Mideast peace
process which took off 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Barak visited Cairo before when he was foreign minister in the
previous Labor government.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Barak is expected to discuss with
Egyptian officials on Egypt's fresh proposals to salvage the peace
process which came to a halt after Israel broke ground for the
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in
March.
</P>
<P>
Both U.S. and Egyptian efforts have so far failed to get the
two sides back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party decided two months ago to recognize the
Palestinians' right to self-determination and leave open the
possibility of establishing a Palestinian state, which has been
adamantly rejected by the Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was elected on June 4 to succeed former Labor Party
leader Shimon Peres, is widely regarded as the only person that
could pose a strong challenge to Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Now the Labor is working to mobilize Israeli public opinion for
an early election which many hope will bring it back to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
