<HEADLINE> S.Africa's Cellular Network Achieves Fast Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Vodacom, one of South
Africa's two leading cellular network operators, has experienced
a fast growth, achieving its 10-year economic development
commitments in just three years.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom Managing Director Alan Knott-Craig said here today the
cellular network had surpassed its one billion Rand (about 222
million US Dollar) credit commitment to the government negotiated
as part of its cellular licence agreement.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom had undertaken to contribute one billion Rand in
development generating activity within 10 years, and deploy some
22,000 phones in underserviced areas within five years.
</P>
<P>
Knott-Craig said Vodacom had already earned more than one
billion Rand in development "credits" and was currently on target
with the rollout of community service telephones.
</P>
<P>
The phenomenal growth of the cellular industry in South Africa
would continue into the next century, and new cellular
connections could exceed fixed line connections as early as next
year, he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the cellular industry in South Africa
breached the one million subscriber mark in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications and Broadcasting Minister Jay Naidoo had
said the communications sector was set to become the driving
force of the South African economy, and formed the backbone of
the African technological "renaissance". 
</P>
</TEXT>
