<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-15 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Hold Elections Despite Opposition's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian government today
reiterated it will hold the parliamentary elections as scheduled
despite opposition's boycott threat.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a recent statement by opposition party the
Muslim Brotherhood to boycott the elections, a government
spokesman told Radio Jordan that the elections will be held as
scheduled in November no matter the Muslim Brotherhood
participates or not,
</P>
<P>
The opposition party`s general supervisor Abdul Majeed Thneibat
said Saturday that the Press and Publication Law, the
one-person-one-vote election system, the normalization of ties
with Israel and "the government`s measures to marginalize
political parties" were the main reasons behind the movement`s
decision to boycott the 1997 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition parties, including the biggest one the
Islamic Action Front, are also considering to go after the
Muslim Brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
The government spokesman stated that the government`s
committment to hold the elections on time is based on voluntary,
irreversible option of broadening the basis of constitutional
democracy as a way of political life in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The true committment to democracy of the government requires
the respect to the opinion of the minority, but this does not
contradict with making decision in accordance with the majority`s
opinion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Publication and Press Law passed by the government in May
has forced most weekly tabloids to close down. The government
accused the publications of instigating sectarianism and
destructing the image of the state and its institutions.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that if these malfunctions were not addressed,
it would lead to the collapse of social values.
</P>
<P>
As to the one-person-one-vote election system, the spokesman
said that it was endorsed by a comfortable majority in
Parliament, which meant that it was not controversial as it
looked in the Muslim Botherhood`s statement.
</P>
<P>
As to Jordan`s peace treaty with Israel that was concluded in
1994, the spokesman said that the government does not see any link
between it and the call to stay away from the elections, because
the peace treaty was also approved by Parliament and went through
all its constitutional stages.
</P>
<P>
The government still believes that the Muslim Brotherhood is
a political spectrum in Jordan, but it should rethink its decision
to boycott the elections, the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
