<HEADLINE> Palestinian Official: Peace Would Be Finally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 15 (Xinhua) - A visiting top Palestinian official
said here today that the Palestinians will finally be able to
reach peace with Israel, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
"Eventually justice would prevail and Israel will be forced to
accept what it had signed", the political advisor to Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat, Mohammod Abbas, told the press after
holding talks with Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam Majali
here today.
</P>
<P>
Abbas also renewed the Palestinians` demand that Israel stop
its hostile activities in the West Bank and urged it to resume
peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Implementing peace accords is an international responsibility
since several countries were involved in its developments,
Abbas added.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the political advisor, who arrived here
Monday on a short visit, briefed Majali on his recent meetings
with Israeli officials and his visits to some Arab countries as
part of the Palestinian efforts to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also exchanged views on the latest developments of
the peace process and means to overcome the hurdles in achieving
a just, lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Jordan mediated the Hebron accord in January this year, under
which Israel promised to evacuate most areas of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But the peace process stalled Later in March when Israel began
to build Jewish settlements in the Arab East Jerusalem that
sparked violent protests of the Palestinians who take the city as
their future capital. 
</P>
