<HEADLINE> Concept for White Homeland Discussed in S.Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Liu Yegang)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) has held talks on possibility of
setting up an Afrikaner homeland with the rightwing Freedom
Front, ANC officials said here today.
</P>
<P>
They said the talks were successful, adding that ANC Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki and Freedom Front leader Constand Viljoen
were leading the talks yesterday in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"This is the start of a process, but not something in which
one can expect immediate answer, solutions or agreement," Freedom
Front chief whip Joseph Chiole said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The Freedom Front's top policy structure, its Federal Council,
last year decided to negotiate with the ANC on a package of
proposals to give concrete efforts to the principle of setting up
the Afrikaner homeland in the constitution.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front officials said the party will be seeking
agreement in principle to the creation of an Afrikaner homeland,
or an ANC acceptance of an Afrikaner homeland as a solution to
the culture and political aspirations of the white community.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela said last year that he
was ready to accept the concept of Afrikaner homeland, but he
will discuss the matter with other political parties.
</P>
<P>
Chiole said yesterday the talks between Mbeki and Viljoen
started the drive for "Afrikaner self-determination".
</P>
<P>
Afrikaners are mostly descendants of the Dutch settlers who
set foot in South Africa in the 1650s.
</P>
<P>
Their leaders introduced apartheid in the country in 1948,
which was abolished with the all-race general elections in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
