<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Busy Parents Blamed for Rising Numbers of Shy Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of people who consider
themselves shy has increased by 20 percent over the past 15 years
and the reason for that is nowadays children are neglected and
given too little time by their busy parents, according to a
psychology conference.
</P>
<P>
The four-day conference on shyness at Cardiff University was
told Monday that the number of people growing into shy adults has
risen because their parents spend an average of only eight minutes
a day talking to them as they are too involved in their busy
lives.
</P>
<P>
The conference heard that parents' neglect of their children
comes at a vital time in their lives and most children become shy
when they reach adolescence, between 11 and 14, which are the
years when they need most help from their parents.
</P>
<P>
Studies in the early 1970s showed that 40 percent of adults
felt that shyness was affecting their behavior, but recent studies
put the figure at between 55 and 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
The conference, run by the British Psychological Society,
called on parents to find time for their children, because
otherwise, children are going to spend more and more of their time
alone in their bedrooms and they cannot acquire social skills to
enable them to relate to people.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the conference is Britain's first one on
shyness and is attended by 70 researchers from all over the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
