<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Minister Confronts Parliament Grilling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's parliament and
cabinet run into confrontation today as Deputy Prime Minister and
Financial Minister Naser Al-Roudhan fiercely fought back the
interpellation by liberal parliament members.
</P>
<P>
The parliament grilling was riddled with "gaps and faults, it
derailed from pertinence and is full of exaggeration, defamation
and false charges," Al-Roudhan said.
</P>
<P>
Three members of the Kuwaiti National Assembly staged an open
questioning against Al-Roudhan over alleged mismanagement,
irregularities in handling public funds and negligence.
</P>
<P>
The financial minister is now chairing the Kuwait Investment
Authority which manages the state's foreign investments of about
40 billion U.S. dollars, the Central Bank and the Kuwait Airways.
</P>
<P>
Those who initiated the grilling were aimed at "overthrowing
the government," retorted Al-Roudhan.
</P>
<P>
Insisting his hands were clean from any ill-gotten gains, he
said the grilling was "strange in its timing, circumstances,
content, subjects, language and objectives."
</P>
<P>
All the three parliament members took floor to question the
minister on a number of accusations, including his failure to
retrieve a sum of 25 million dollars deposited in a "Tunisian bank
suffering from financial problems."
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the interrogation motion, the first since
the election of the current parliament in October 1996, was
necessary for "it reflects the public opinion's keenness on
protecting public funds."
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwaiti Acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah earlier this month played
down the questioning, saying it was "nothing more than the
exercise of a constitutional right."
</P>
<P>
Twenty four lawmakers have filed 12 grilling motions in nearly
four decades since Kuwait exercises legislative democracy, leading
to the resignation of only one government minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
