<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abnormal High Cholesterol Popular in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has the highest
incidence of familial hypercholesterolaemia (FH) in the world,
according to a survey by pharmaceutical laboratories in Cape
Town.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 120,000 South Africans have abnormal high
cholesterol and are in danger of developing serious and possibly
fatal heart disease.
</P>
<P>
"Yet of these, only 5,000 have been identified and only about
half of them are receiving treatment," the laboratories said in a
joint statement, noting that most of these sufferers were in the
Asian, Afrikaans and Jewish communities in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
They are the inheritors of a gene which prevents correct
processing of cholesterol, causing it to collect in the blood
stream, deposit on the walls of blood vessels, and lead to heart
attacks, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that a belief that only overweight
people will develop high blood cholesterol was not true, saying
many people with high cholesterol were slim, trim, fit and
followed a prudent diet.
</P>
<P>
High cholesterol is the major risk factor for heart disease, but it
is not as dangerous on its own as when it is associated with
other risk factors, such as being male, smoking, high blood
pressure and stress.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the condition is identified and managed adequately,
men tend to have heart attacks in their 30s and 40s, and women
have heart attacks in their 40s and 50s," medical workers warned.
</P>
<P>
The only way to control high cholesterol is drug therapy, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Car Sales in UK Expected to Increase in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The UK motor industry is looking
forward to a healthy increase in new car sales this August, helped
by cash windfalls from building societies converting to banks.
</P>
<P>
The all-time high for new car sales in August was back in the
long hot summer of 1989 when 500,112 units were registered.
Altogether 2.3 million cars were sold that year.
</P>
<P>
The recession which followed hit annual sales of new cars quite
hard, but there has been a steady rise since 1993, back up
towards the 2 million mark which was passed last year.
</P>
<P>
The motor industry is looking for sales of around 490,000 in
August, which should pass 2.1 million sales by the end of the
year, according to a forecast by the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders Limited.
</P>
<P>
It also said this year could well be the last time that
customers wait up until midnight on August 1 for their new
registration letter because the "year identifier" might soon be a
thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
As a tradition, around one quarter of all sales are made in
August, which puts enormous strain on the supply chain to fulfill
customers' requirements exactly.
</P>
<P>
Very often the customer is forced to take the vehicle which is
available rather than the exact model wanted.
</P>
<P>
The UK motor industry agrees that the letter should change
twice a year on 1 March and 1 September starting in 1998. So look
out for `S' reg next spring and `T' reg in the autumn.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Government is looking at the proposal right now and
customers are waiting for the go ahead any day. If the system
receives the green light now, then car owners will start the new
run next March, and that will take customers to September 2001.
</P>
<P>
Historically the letter changed on 1 January which caused a
huge build-up in sales, so manufacturers proposed a year
identifier change to 1 June. The retailers wanted 1 October.
</P>
<P>
The government compromised and decreed 1 August, at the time it
was a month with few sales (typically 7 percent of annual sales).
The revised system has been in operation since 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
