<HEADLINE> Statue of Egypt's Pharaoh Ramses II to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian archaeological
sub-committee decided today to return the statue of Ramsis II, one
of Egypt's greatest pharaohs, to its original home village in
Rahina, Giza, south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The selection of the resting place for the colossal was made
after months of heated debate and careful scientific research that
negated other two options, the Egyptian Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 125-tonne and 11.4-meter-high rosy granite statue was
unearthed in Rahina, the ancient Egyptian capital of Menf in 1888.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that Rahina, an area free of pollution, is the
best possible choice for the statue, which has graced a Cairo
square bearing his name for 43 years.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the sanctuary could spare the status its present
daily sufferings of erosion, air pollution and the vibrations of
the metro operating underneath.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Culture Farouq Hosni, also head of the
Higher Antiquities Council, told reporters today that a
comprehensive plan will be implemented to develop Rahina into a
fully-equipped tourist and archeological resort.
</P>
<P>
Ramsis II, whose reign (1304-1237 BC) was the second longest in
Egyptian history, lived for 95 years. He had eight wives, 52 sons
and 48 daughters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
