<HEADLINE> EU May Ban Importing Nile Perch From Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
granted Tanzania more time to improve the quality of the Lake
Victoria Nile Perch, otherwise may ban its imports in its member
states by February 28 next year.
</P>
<P>
Christian Herbin, the first counselor in the EU delegation in
Tanzania, told reporters here today that the EU Commission has
extended its decision on announcing the ban or continuing to
import the Nile Perch from July 1 this year to next February 28.
</P>
<P>
In April this year traces of Salmonella and pesticides were
detected in the Nile Perch in EU member states and this led to a
team of experts from EU to come to Tanzania and inspected four
fish processing plants at Mwanzan and Musoma in northwestern
Tanzania, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important that exporters send the right Nile Perch or
else they will get huge loss if a container is detected at the
point of entry to have a bad product, it will be destroyed," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Herbin explained that since detection of poor quality Nile
Perch from Lake Victoria shared by Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, EU
member states were allowed to individually deal directly with
exporting countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
