<HEADLINE> Germany, US Plan Joint Missile Defense Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The German Defense Ministry said
today that Germany and the Unites States would sign an accord
later this year to complete the building of a joint air defense
unit in 1999 with a view to strengthening their post-cold war
military ties.
</P>
<P>
The US military presence in Europe has been declining since the
fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989, with American forces
based in Europe reduced to about 100,000 now from 336,000.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Bonn is increasingly concerned over the threat of
short- and medium-range missiles which could be fired from the
Middle East at European targets.
</P>
<P>
"Besides the German, American and a small number of Dutch
systems, there are no further Patriot systems in the entire NATO
alliance," said the Defense Ministry statement. "This is the only
system which at present offers limited protection against tactical
ballistic missiles."
</P>
<P>
The first ever fully integrated German-American forces, modeled
on a 5,000-man Franco-German armored brigade, will comprise 500
troops armed with Patriot, Hawk and Roland air defense missile
systems.
</P>
<P>
The joint forces would be available for deployment with
international peacekeeping missions under the approval of both
sides, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Press reports said that commandership of the joint unit would
rotate every three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
