<HEADLINE> Algerian Government Releases Top Islamic Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Algerian government today
released the country's top Islamic leader, Abassi Madani, who was
the number one of the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) before it was
outlawed in March 1992.
</P>
<P>
The decision, made by a military tribunal of Blida south of
Algiers, was announced early this morning, according to reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Madani, 66, was arrested in June 1991 for launching an appeal
for general strike after the Algerian army canceled the results of
the second round of legislative elections, in which the FIS got
most of the votes. He was condemned to 12 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
The cancelation of election results triggered a war between
government forces and Islamic militants over the past six years,
in which at least 60,000 people were killed, according to
estimations made by Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Madani's release came one week after another key FIS leader,
Abderkader Hachani, was released from jail. It also coincided with
a wave of terrorist attacks in Algeria over the past five days, in
which 120 people were reportedly killed.
</P>
<P>
But some observers said that the release was both a clemency
from President Liamine Zeroual and an indication that Zeroual has
consolidated power after his supporters won an absolute majority
in the legislative elections on June 5.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the political scenery of Algeria today is totally
different from that six years ago: FIS's political network has
been completely dismantled and what remains of its leadership is
living in exile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0034 </DOCNO>
