<HEADLINE> E. African NGOs dealing with AIDS Open Office in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Network of Non-Governmental
Organizations (NGOs) in East Africa region (ANNEA) dealing with
Acquired Immuno Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) has opened an office
at Arusha in Northern Tanzania, which will cater for the region.
</P>
<P>
A networking official, Susan Malya told the Tanzania News
Agency at Arusha today that the role of the office will be to
coordinate the fight AIDS activities in the three east African
countries which are among the badly affected nations in Africa.
</P>
<P>
She said that ANNEA was founded in 1994 by 19 AIDS related
NGOs from Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania to fill the gap of lack of
collaboration and coordination which have been the drawbacks to
the success of the NGOs ever since the organization has had no
permanent office.
</P>
<P>
According to the June 1997 Newsletter by the organization, the
region enjoys the existence of many NGOs formed to complement
government efforts to fight the AIDS scourge. The newsletter
entitled "ANNEA newsletter" reports that each of the three
countries had 42,000 AIDS cases so far.
</P>
<P>
While the first case in the region was reported in 1982, the
cumulative new infections according to the newsletter is very
alarming as it stands today.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's projection are 2.4 million HIV infected people,
800,000 AIDS cases and 450,000 to one million orphans by the year
2000, while Kenya projects to have 1.5 million HIV infected cases
by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has reported a cumulative new HIV infection on 673,000
adults and 294,000 children below 15 years from 1993-1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
