<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians' Incomes Unchanged in 1995 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Canadians reported a median total
income of 18,900 Canadian dollars (13,800 US dollars) in 1995, up
400 dollars (292 US dollars) from 1994, Statistics Canada reported
today.
</P>
<P>
However, adjusting for inflation, "there was virtually no
change from a year earlier," the federal agency noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the gap between men and women narrowed slightly as
median total income fell for men and increased for women.
</P>
<P>
The national median for men declined marginally to 25,400
dollars (18,540 US dollars) in 1995 from 25,433 dollars (18,560 US
dollars) a year earlier, with inflation taken into account.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the median for women rose to 14,600 dollars
(10,660 US dollars) from 14,504 dollars (10,590 US dollars), a 0.7
percent increase compared with a gain of 4.0 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Total income for Canadians comprises employment income,
investment income, transfer payments, retirement savings and other
income.
</P>
<P>
Median income represents the middle point at which half the
incomes are above and half are below the median. 
</P>
</TEXT>
