<HEADLINE> S. Leonean Junta Cabinet Sworn In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
FREETOWN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Eight secretaries of state of
the Sierra Leone junta took an oath for office Monday before
their military leader Major Johnny Paul Koroma here in the
capital#,state television reported today.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet is headed by Koroma with Foday Sankoh as deputy
head of state. The latter has been the leader of the rebel
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) who is detained in Nigeria under
unexplained circumstances.
</P>
<P>
All the secretaries of state or ministers were appointed by
Koroma last week.
</P>
<P>
Captain Solomon Musa, a one time chief secretary in the
military regime of Captain Valentine Strasser who left office in
1996, again becomes the chief secretary or prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The entire cabinet has six civilians and seven military
officers, two of whom are retired officials and five from the
people's army.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the cabinet secretariat said, the remaining
five secretaries of state will take their oath shortly.
</P>
<P>
The portfolio of foreign secretary goes to Paolo Bangura,
formerly Sierra Leonean ambassador to the United Nations while
the attorney general is Manley Spaine. Finance Secretary Joe
Amara Bangali has held a similar position under the civilian
government of Siaka Stevens in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Koromah told the cabinet members
that since they have accepted "a huge responsibility to serve the
nation at this crucial period, you cannot afford to fail."
</P>
<P>
The junta's Secretary General Colonel Abdul Sesay hailed the
occasion which "officially confirms the establishment of the
(military) government and ministers are now empowered to fulfil
their fullest responsibility."
</P>
<P>
Political observers analysed that the background of the new
ministers and their rich experiences will help the junta grapple
with many urgent tasks that need solutions quickly, which include
getting the country back to its economic track and embarking on
negotiations to return the country back to civilian rule.
</P>
<P>
A Sierra Leone delegation headed by Solomon Musa is expected
to leave for Cote d'Ivoire on July 17 to start talks on the
formation of a broad based government that will take on board all
interested parties to end the current political impasse,
political analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Major Victor King, the new secretary of state,
accused the ousted government headed by Tejan Kabbah of
"injustice, nepotism and mismanagement of state funds", which
consequently brought forth the May 25 takeover.
</P>
<P>
Addressing administrative staff today at the state house, he
blamed former President Kabbah for "neglecting his own military
forces by bringing in Nigerians to serve as bodyguards with a
monthly salary of 2,000 U.S Dollars, whereas Sierra Leonean
soldiers who have been in the war front, received a salary of 15
Dollars with only a bag of rice."
</P>
<P>
Nine of the 13 under-secretaries of state including Matilda
King, a women, were also sworn in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
