attack by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) on
suspected Bosnian Serb war criminals.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters before a White House meeting with
congressional leaders, Clinton said that any retaliation would be
a "grave mistake."
</P>
<P>
"They have no call to take any retaliatory action and it would
be a grave mistake to do so," he said.
</P>
<P>
During an operation last week, British soldiers of the alliance
arrested one Bosnian Serb and killed another. The two were charged
by the West with war crimes during the Bosnian civil war.
</P>
<P>
Since the swoop, tensions have been high on the Bosnian Serb
territories against international monitors.
</P>
<P>
A bomb exploded Sunday night, destroying a pick-up truck
outside offices belonging to the international monitors.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he was worried about possible backlash from the
Bosnian Serbs, Clinton said, "I am concerned about it, of course I
am. But the representatives of the Serbs signed the Dayton
agreement."
</P>
<P>
"The Dayton agreement says that if someone is charged with a
war crime, they should be turned over for trial," Clinton added.
</P>
