<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Promises New Air Safety Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- United States Vice President Al
Gore and transportation officials today promised new air-safety
measures, including the installation of 500 systems for checking
baggage for explosives.
</P>
<P>
"No matter how safe aviation is, we must make it even safer,
said Gore at a press conference at suburban Washington's Dulles
airport, where he received an updated catalogue of steps taken by
the National Aeroautics and Space Administration (NASA) and the
Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) to tighten airline safety.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken shortly before the anniversary of the
crash of the Trans World Airlines (TWA) flight, which killed all
230 people aboard. The TWA 800 crash on last July 17 off New York
City was widely believed by an explosion that originated in a
nearly empty center fuel tank.
</P>
<P>
Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater said that by the end of
this year the FAA will finish work on new regulations requiring
smoke detectors and fire-extinguishing devices in the cargo and
baggage compartments of large jetliners.
</P>
<P>
He also promised hiring of 375 additional inspectors to
increase security oversight at airports nationwide and awarding of
contracts to purchase more than 480 trace-explosive detection
devices, plus some 20 automated dual energy X-ray machines.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the NASA Aviation Safety Program, a joint
initiative of NASA, the FAA, Defense Department and airline
industry, also showed new safety technologies.
</P>
<P>
The technologies include systems for finding cracks in aging
planes, for allowing pilots to navigate in near-zero visibility
conditions and for giving pilots advance weather information.
</P>
</TEXT>
