<HEADLINE> Ambassador Hails Nigeria's Leadership in W. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Ambassador to Liberia
Joshua Iroha today said his country's efforts for security in
west Africa is just for leadership and should be viewed as
investment for benefits.
</P>
<P>
Whatever sacrifice Nigeria might have made to ensure normalcy
in the west African sub-region is a necessary price for
leadership, Iroha said in Monrovia, capital of Liberia.
</P>
<P>
"No one could lead from behind and whoever is in front must
justify the prominence that position conferred on him," the envoy
said, quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Iroha did not elaborate on the sacrifice Nigeria has made but
observers noted it has some connections with the country's
contribution to the sub-region's peace-keeping operations
particularly in Liberia and Sierra Leone recently.
</P>
<P>
During the operation in Liberia in the past seven years,
Nigeria shouldered the bulk of billions of Dollars of financial
expenditure, materials and more than 10,000 peace-keeping troops.
</P>
<P>
The operation has resulted in the successful disarmament and
demobilization of Liberia's warring factions, paving the way for
the post-war elections in the tiny west African country.
</P>
<P>
The Nigeria-led west African peacekeeping force known as
ECOMOG is now in firm control of that country, providing a
favorable environment for a free and fair election scheduled for
July 19.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were also sent to Sierra Leone in a bid to
restore the elected civilian government that was toppled in a
military coup on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Repeated fightings have been reported between ECOMOG troops
and soldiers loyal to Sierra Leone's military government, with
casualties from both sides.
</P>
<P>
If all this is related to Nigeria's sacrifice, "such a
sacrifice should be seen as an investment whose benefits might
come early or later," said Iroha.
</P>
<P>
As to what Nigeria can do to derive some benefits from a
country for which it has done so much, Iroha said Nigeria should
assist interested and suitable Nigerian outfits to go and operate
in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The success of such outfits would have a positive effect on
the Nigerian economy by enhancing its growth and contribution to
its prosperity, he said.
</P>
<P>
The envoy suggested that early planning would help achieve
this type of objective as restoring to ad hoc measures much later
would not produce the desired result. 
</P>
</TEXT>
