<HEADLINE> Rules on Indirect Taxation Be Uniform in EU: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Steps have to be taken to ensure
that the current rules governing indirect taxation are applied
uniformly throughout the European Union (EU), an EU official said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Mario Monti, EU commissioner responsible for taxation, made
the remark after the EU's executive body, the European Commission,
proposed a new procedure for the adoption of certain implementing
measures relating to indirect taxation.
</P>
<P>
The EC Tuesday proposed that the directive on the common system
of VAT (value-added tax) and that on the general arrangements for
products subject to excise duty be amended so as to give the
Commission wider implementing power that would be exercised
together with the committees representative of EU member states.
</P>
<P>
Following the adoption of general rules by the European Council
in consultation with the European Parliament, detailed technical
provisions would be adopted by the EC if the relevant committee
approved the draft proposal.
</P>
<P>
These implementing measures should ensure uniform application
of the directives, particularly in those areas where the
possibility of differing interpretations might undermine the
smooth functioning of the single market, according to the EC.
</P>
<P>
At present, the common systems of VAT and excise duty are
applied differently from one member country to another, which is
incompatible with the single market concept.
</P>
<P>
Traders are suffering as a result of this legal uncertainty and
the frequent cases of double taxation of cross frontier
transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales in US Up by 0.5 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in the U.S. rose
by 0.5 percent in June, reversing three straight declines, the
U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that retail sales totaled a seasonally
adjusted 210.3 billion dollars last month, up from 209.3 billion
in May.
</P>
<P>
Sales of durable goods -- items expected to last more than
three years -- were up 0.5 percent in June after falling 0.9
percent a month earlier. Auto dealers posted a 1.1 percent gain in
the month. Excluding autos, sales rose 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nondurable goods such as food and fuel rose 0.4 percent, also
the third increase in a row.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales in the U.S. declined in March, April and May. The
three consecutive drops signaled the end of what had been a
consumer spending spree that propelled the economy at a sizzling
5.9 percent annual rate during the January-March quarter.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales, about one-third of the nation's economic
activity, had shot up 1.6 percent in January and 1.3 percent in
February.
</P>
<P>
The drop of retail sales in the past months was a major signal
that the U.S. economy was slowing down and more moderate economic
growth recently has permitted U.S. Federal Reserve policy-makers
to leave interest rates unchanged, rather than boost them to keep
inflation under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
