<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Doctors and pharmacists are
continue their strikes today in protest against the Greek
government's plan aimed at restructuring the National Health
System (ESY).
</P>
<P>
Greek Health Minister Costas Geitonas today submitted a bill to
the Parliament with the aim of reforming the ESY. The bill has
provoked a storm of protest and three weeks of strikes by doctors
employed by the state system.
</P>
<P>
Doctors argued that the key problems were their salaries and
the fact that newly-hired doctors would not enjoy permanent status
right from the start.
</P>
<P>
Pharmacists said that the government's plan would trim their
profit margins on medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government today stressed that it would persist in
its policy of reducing the retail price of medicines.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that in order to
reduce retail prices, the government was making an effort to
overhaul the entire system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
