<HEADLINE> Nairobi Stock Trading Active </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi Stock Exchange (NSE)
Monday sold 766,000 shares valued at 31.5 million Kenyan
Shillings (about 540,000 U.S. Dollars), up from last Friday's
365,000 shares valued at 18 million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Trading at the stock exchange declined last week to 93.2
million Shillings from the previous week's turnover of 170
million.
</P>
<P>
Last week the total number of shares traded fell by 50 percent
from 3.8 million shares the previous week to 1.98 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Trading at the NSE floor started on a low note on Monday last
week with only eight broking houses participating in the trading
as others opted to close due to the Saba Saba (July 7) reform
rallies and riots in the country.
</P>
<P>
The NSE share index lost 0.92 points to close at 3502.76 last
Friday when share recorded marginal fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
However, brokers predicted that trading was expected to pick
up this week as last Friday President Daniel arap Moi announced
that he would convene the ruling Kenya African National Union
delegates conference and the Governing Council meeting to
deliberate on the issue of constitutional reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
