<HEADLINE> Britain Remains Ban on Contacts with Sinn Fein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The British government said today
it had not changed its decision to ban official talks with the
IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, despite renewed contacts with the
latter.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Northern Ireland Office said: "There has
been no change in policy because we have said there would be no
meetings and there have not been any meetings."
</P>
<P>
Britain severed official contacts with Sinn Fein on June 16
after IRA gunmen shot and killed two policemen on the street in a
daylight ambush.
</P>
<P>
But Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam acknowledged on Monday
that officials had been in touch with Sinn Fein after the group
initiated the contact seeking clarification of the requirements
for its admission to peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman explained that the contacts with Sinn Fein were
undertaken in writing form and on telephone. "At no point could
this be seen as a negotiation," she added.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has been barred from attending the multi-party peace
talks since February of last year when IRA quit a 17-month
ceasefire. British Prime Minister Tony Blair has said Sinn Fein
can only join peace talks if it persuades its Irish Republican
Army allies to lay down arms and call for a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks resumed today in the provincial capital Belfast
with preliminary discussions before a plenary session on
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
