<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM Says Foreign Policy to Look East and West </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov today denied any direct link between the North Atlantic
Treat Organization's (NATO) eastward expansion, which Russia
opposes, and more active Russian diplomacy in the East, the Itar-Tass
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to journalists with leading Japanese newspapers,
Primakov said that despite NATO expansion, Russia should pay more
attention to developing ties with countries in the east in view of
the movement towards a multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
Primakov also reiterated Russia's objection to NATO's plans to
expand eastward to take in countries from the former Warsaw
Pact. "We are against NATO's enlargement to the east. We don't
conceal it and we are not changing our stand."
</P>
<P>
At a summit in Madrid earlier this month, NATO invited Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join the military alliance. The
three countries hope to become new members of NATO in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Russia opposes NATO's expansion into eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union states, and believes European security should
be safeguarded by promoting mutual trust among regional countries
instead of by NATO enlargement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
