<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Says EU Enlargement Outweighs NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Early membership of the European
Union for the three Baltic states and Poland is more important for
European security than NATO enlargement, Swedish Foreign Minister
Lena Hjelm-Wallen said in a newspaper commentary today.
</P>
<P>
Writing in Dagens Nyheter, the minister said EU enlargement
would reduce the dangers of creating new borders in a post-Cold
War Europe and was a key factor in achieving European security.
</P>
<P>
She welcomed NATO enlargement and reform as a move away from
the defense of western democracies toward ensuring the security of
Europe as a whole.
</P>
<P>
But although NATO's military security guarantees for its
members were essential in the context of war, they were not
central to ensuring the general security of Europe.
</P>
<P>
She added that the biggest threat to European security would by
and large cease to be military and therefore NATO's expansion into
central and eastern Europe was not a crucial issue.
</P>
<P>
Hjelm-Wallen said Sweden would support Estonia, Latvia,
Lithuania and Poland to be among the first batch of countries
invited to join the EU early next century.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission -- the EU's executive body -- agreed on
Tuesday to recommend the Czech Republic, Estonia, Hungary, Poland,
Slovenia and the Mediterranean island country of Cyprus as the
first wave of countries to take part in EU membership talks
beginning next year. Reports said Latvia and Lithuania were not
included because of economic problems.
</P>
<P>
But the plan has to be approved by the heads of government of
all EU members at a meeting in December when the final decision
about who will be in the first wave will be made.
</P>
<P>
Sweden, a neutral country in the Baltic since the early 19th
century, has faced growing domestic pressure for a seat within
NATO.
</P>
<P>
But Hjelm-Wallen said Sweden would stay out of any such
military alliance but would continue its cooperation within NATO's
Partnership for Peace program -- a cooperation program with former
eastern bloc countries and other European non-NATO countries on
regional defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
