<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Opposition Leader Pledges to Serve Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak promised here today that he will reopen talks on
further Israeli redeployment and security cooperation with the
Palestinians if he is elected prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Barak made the pledge after a meeting with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak and Foreign Minister Amr Moussa. However, he skirted
the more controversial issue of settlement building.
</P>
<P>
Barak, on the second day of his two-day visit here, told
reporters that he would have taken into account the Israel's
security concern and other parties' interests if he was in the
shoes of incumbent Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu who has been
blamed for his obsession with Israel's sole interest.
</P>
<P>
"I would have revived immediately cooperation between the
Israeli and the Palestinian security authorities and allowed
the Palestinian police access to the Hebron cordon to help quell
street violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I would have also done my utmost to resume negotiations over
the second stage of re-deployment which should have been done some
months ago," he said.
</P>
<P>
Under a timetable outlined in a January Palestinian-Israeli
agreement on Hebron redeployment, the second phase of the
three-stage Israeli troop withdrawal from the West Bank should
start in March and the last be completed no later than mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
When answered questions on his plans to improve economic
conditions for the Palestinians if he becomes prime minister,
Barak said he believes there is a long way ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Labor leader expressed hope of good neighborly relations
with the Palestinians in the future when pending problems are solved.
</P>
<P>
"Neighbors, like parents, cannot be chosen. We have to work on
developing mutual respect and cooperation and creating a good
relationship as neighbors, and proof of this is our relationship
with Egypt," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy is clear, we want to separate from the Palestinians and
we want them to define their identity and shape their lives while
taking into consideration the security of Israel," he added.
</P>
<P>
But he deliberately avoided the settlement issue, saying that
"it is improper to comment on it in Cairo."
</P>
<P>
He said the Labor party strongly believes in "Israel's right
to build settlements, but not on Arab-owned lands."
</P>
<P>
"We also believe that through the final status negotiations,
most of the settlements, not necessarily all of them, should come
under Israel's sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party decided in May to recognize the Palestinians'
right to self-determination and leave open the possibility of
establishing a Palestinian state, which has been adamantly
rejected by Israel's Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was elected on June 4 to succeed former Labor Party
leader Shimon Peres, is widely regarded as the only person that
could pose a strong challenge to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Now the Labor is working to mobilize Israeli public opinion for
an early election which many hope will bring it back to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
