<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC President Urges Improved EU World Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Santer, president of the
European Commission, today urged the European Union (EU) countries
to seize the opportunity of enlargement to improve its economy and
status in the world.
</P>
<P>
In presenting a communication today to the European Parliament,
the president of the EU's executive agency said, "Enlargement
represents a historic turning point for Europe, an opportunity
which it must seize for the sake of its security, its economy, its
culture and its status in the world."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the EU's internal and external environments
were both changing fast and that it must set about "adapting,
developing and reforming itself."
</P>
<P>
The commission today submitted the communication entitled
Agenda 2000, together with opinions on each of the applications
for EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The publication constitutes the commission's comprehensive
response to requests from the European Council meeting in Madrid
in December of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Taking account of the prospect of an enlarged EU, the
commission outlines the broad outlook for the EU's development and
its policies beyond the turn of the century, the impact of
enlargement on the EU as a whole and the future financial
framework beyond 2000.
</P>
<P>
The commission maintained that the negotiations on EU
membership should start with six candidate countries -- Hungary,
Poland, Estonia, the Czech Republic, Slovenia and Cyprus,
according to Santer.
</P>
<P>
Finally, Santer said that it would not be necessary to resort
to an increase of the actual budgetary ceiling -- 1.27 percent of
GDP of the union -- in order to face the multiple challenges.
</P>
</TEXT>
