<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Schlappner Resigns as Vanguard Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, Central China, July 16 (Xinhua) -- German Klaus
Schlappner has resigned as the coach for China's Professional
League side Vanguard Huandao on Wednesday, becoming the second
coach to quit in four days in the league.
</P>
<P>
Schlappner, who had made Chinese soccer history by becoming the
first foreigner to coach the Chinese national team in early 1990s,
submitted his letter of resignation to the Vanguard management
Tuesday morning, the club said.
</P>
<P>
A club spokesman said the 56-year-old Schlappner told the club
in his letter that the pressure in the coming second half of the
season would be too much for him as the performance of the team
was far from satisfactory in the first nine of the 22 rounds.
</P>
<P>
He was replaced by Vanguard's team leader Yan Dejun but like a
Bulgarian who quit as Shanghai Shenhua coach on Sunday, stays in
the team as an advisor.
</P>
<P>
Yan told Xinhua that his top priority is to prevent Vanguard,
now eighth in the 12-team league, from being relegated.
</P>
<P>
Schlappner took over the Chinese national squad on June 15,
1992. He was fired by the Chinese Football Association after the
team failed to qualify for the second stage in the Asian
qualifying tournament for the 1994 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
He returned to Germany to train second-division side Waldhof
Mannheim last season and returned to China to coach Vanguard since
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
