<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Lower Borrowing Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' top monetary
official said today the central bank is to lower its overnight
borrowing rate to 28 percent Thursday from a four-year high of 32
percent.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Gabriel Singson was quoted by the local
SNN television as saying that the hefty borrowing rate will be
lowered considering the signs of recovery in the foreign currency
market.
</P>
<P>
The central bank hiked its overnight borrowing rate four times
in a week since the start of this month in a bid to repulse
speculative attacks on the Philippine peso. The key interest rate
was lifted to a four-year high of 32 percent from 30 percent last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The television reports said commercial banks are expected to
follow suit and lower their interest rates, which have been
raised following the spiral of the central bank's borrowing rate.
</P>
<P>
Economists have warned that continued high interest rates will
affect corporations and the property sector and then hurt the
local stock market.
</P>
<P>
Due to volatility in the currency market and continued high
interest rates, investors today remained shy away from the local
bourse. The Philippine Stock Exchange composite index (Phisix)
today plummeted by 68.5 points to close at 2,587.36, the lowest
since January 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
