<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Meets With Japan LDP Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Chairman of the Central
Military Commission Chi Haotian hopes Japan will follow a
route of peaceful development and prevent tragedies
from repeating themselves.
</P>
<P>
Chi, who is also State Councilor and Minister of Defense, made
the remarks today when meeting with Koto Koichi, secretary-general
of Japan's Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) on the 25th anniversary
of the normalization of relations between China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Chi said that China and Japan are neighbors separated by a strip
of water and that China has always attached great importance to
the friendly cooperative relations with Japan.
</P>
<P>
The older generation of leaders of the two countries have
thrown all their energy into developing bilateral relations, he
said, and that development momentum of friendly co-operative
relations has maintained over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Promoting the long-term, healthy, stable, friendly
co-operative relations not only conforms to the basic interests of
the two peoples, but is also significant for Asia and the world as
a whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that bilateral relations over the past 25 years were
generally in good shape, despite some ups and downs, and that
three generations of Chinese leaders have emphasized that " past
experience, if not forgotten, is a guide for the future" and that a
correct understanding of history is the basis of development of
relations.
</P>
<P>
However, there are always people in Japan who attempt to deny
historic facts and confound black and white, he said, pointing out
that the Chinese people will not forget history.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to conclude the past, open up the future and establish
Sino-Japanese friendly co-operative relationship on a long-term,
stable and healthy basis, thus maintaining friendship between the
two peoples for generations to come," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chi expressed his concern over the security treaty between
Japan and the United States, and noted that those who fell victim
to Japanese aggression are highly sensitive about this issue, and
he called the so-called "China threat" theory a "sheer
fabrication."
</P>
<P>
Koto said that, generally speaking, bilateral relations have
witnessed smooth development for the past 25 years, and that he
hopes the two sides can continue to increase exchanges and enhance
mutual understanding.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, he said, the cabinet of then Prime-Minister
Tomiichi Murayama made it clear that Japan should be deeply
introspective about its past.  
</P>
</TEXT>
