<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Currency Shows Signs of Normalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso today showed
some signs of normalization, with its exchange rate against the
U.S. dollar appreciating to 29.352 pesos compared with Tuesday's
29.674.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Bankers Association said the reference rate
between the peso and the dollar appreciated by 31 centavos today
as against Tuesday's trading.
</P>
<P>
But on black markets which re-surfaced only several days ago,
the peso was trading 30 to 33 pesos to one dollar, the local SNN
television reported.
</P>
<P>
Volume turnover transacted at the Philippine Dealing System
increased slightly to 23.25 million dollars from Tuesday's 18.35
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The central bank today sold 4 million dollars to help stabilize
the peso, which has devalued more than 11 percent since the bank
announced the peso's floatation last Friday.
</P>
<P>
At his weekly press conference, President Fidel Ramos today
said the floating of the peso has normalized after a frenzy
speculative attack by investors.
</P>
<P>
"There is now limited buying and selling but a lower rate is
being seen, " he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is not going to revise its economic
targets for the year, including those for inflation, economic
growth and budget surplus, despite the attacks on the peso.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from central bank governor Gabriel Singson,
Ramos said officials of HongkongBank Manila assessed that
commercial banks are now more confident that the peso has
stabilized at a range of 29 to 29.50 pesos to one dollar.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also ruled out the possibility of Singson to resign due
to the de facto depreciation of the peso, saying he did not think
Singson should do that. 
</P>
</TEXT>
