<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Leader Praises Role Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Liu Huaqing, vice-chairman of
China's Central Military Commission, has ordered officers and
enlisted men of the People's Liberation Army to learn from Shan
Jie, a soldier who has been helping the Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
Shan is the head of the People's Armed Forces Department of a
small county in the Tibet Autonomous Region. Liu met with him
recently during a visit to the Chengdu Military Area Command, and
spoke of him as a role model.
</P>
<P>
Liu told Shan, "You has been working in Tibet for 28 years,
doing a lot of work for the Tibetan people. What a remarkable job
you have done! But, your parents, your wife and children all live
in Shanghai, so you have faced quite a few difficulties."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Liu, who is a member of the Standing Committee of
the Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee, said that the army as a whole should learn from him.
</P>
<P>
Shan's considerable deeds include mobilizing militia to help
with the economic construction and cultural development there,
helping Tibetans set up a trading company, and giving lectures to
26,000 people on how he serve the people wholeheartedly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
