<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Prison Congestion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is faced with over-congestion in
its prisons where at least 22,675 persons are being detained while
over 15,000 others are in police custody.
</P>
<P>
Quoting an unnamed security chief, the Punch newspaper today reported
that the majority of those in prison were suspects awaiting
trial and the situation has aroused concern from the government.
</P>
<P>
The staggering number of the prison inmates was unacceptable to the
government and some measures were now being devised to stem the trend,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The over-congestion of prison in the country could be attributed
to the fact that the nation's prinsons were built about a century ago
and were designed not to hold more than a quarter of their current
population.
</P>
<P>
However, Nigeria's police boss, Inspector-General of Police Alhaji
Ibrahim Coomassie, expressed disbelief in the staggering figure
released by the security chief.
</P>
<P>
"It's alarming, it shouldn't be so; I will follow it up," Coomassie
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
