<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Muslim Rebel Group Splits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) has broken into two factions, the hawks and the
moderates, due to a profit-sharing struggle, the military said
today.
</P>
<P>
Col. Nestor Castillo, chief of the Armed Forces' Civil
Relations Service (CRS), said that the division came about when
MILF leaders began fighting over shares of fund support generated
from kidnap-for-ransom activities.
</P>
<P>
The MILF leadership squabbles also surfaced over tax collection
and other criminal activities, Castillo said.
</P>
<P>
"Each MILF unit wanted a big slice of the money to support
their logistical needs to support their operations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Quoting military intelligence reports, Castillo also said that
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs, was today
blamed for the debacles and recent battlefield defeats suffered by
the MILF.
</P>
<P>
He said that the MILF Central Committee convened and discussed
courses of action to take by the beleaguered organization.
</P>
<P>
Both Murad and Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for
political affairs, were admonished for betrayal of Islam by
"engaging in activities for personal aggrandizement and enriching
themselves at the expense of the MILF," he said.
</P>
<P>
There is so far no immediate response from the MILF on the
military report.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the larger Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF), which forged a peace deal with the
government last September.
</P>
<P>
The MILF refused to be included in the MNLF-Manila peace accord
and began its own initial peace talks with the government this
January. The rebel group has been accused by the military of being
involved in many kidnap-for-ransom cases.
</P>
<P>
But the MILF withdrew from the peace talks after a major MILF
camp in central Mindanao, the southern Philippines, was overrun by
the military late last month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
