<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Calls for Dialogue on Human Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhu said a lasting impression left by the talks is that people
in those countries know little about the situation in China and
that numerous rumors have resulted in serious misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
Among the rumors that Zhu named are: trials in China are not
open to the public, appeals are not allowed after a court issues a
verdict, and prisoners are executed without investigation into
their cases.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the Tibet issue is just one of the many that are
misinterpreted by the European countries.
</P>
<P>
Zhu cited one media report which asked why school classes in
Tibet have been conducted in Chinese rather than in the Tibetan
language since this year. He called the report "ridiculous."
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the public listens to the propaganda of the Dalai
Lama and his followers, but they do not know that Tibet has not
been an independent state since the 13th century. He added that
Tibet under the Dalai's rule was a serf society more oppressive
than Europe in the Middle Ages.
</P>
<P>
Also, the public does not know that the Dalai was the leading
serf owner in Tibet under whose rule numerous Tibetans and people
of other nationalities were killed. The Dalai is absolutely not an
"angel of peace" who "could not harm a fly."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the public does not know the wishes and hopes of the
more than two million Tibetan people who do not regard the Dalai
as their representative, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu continued that the dialogues conducted by the delegation
during the visit were widely regarded as successful, because all
sides showed their respect for each other and conducted the talks
on an equal footing.
</P>
<P>
All sides participating in the dialogue, including the
representative of Amnesty International, agreed upon the
principles of mutual respect and equality, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said his delegation based its discussions on truth.
</P>
<P>
"We stressed that we do not ask others to accept our opinions,"
Zhu noted. "We just hope they know what our opinions are and why
we have them."
</P>
<P>
He said that when touching on the human rights situation in
China during the talks, the delegation did not dodge the country's
shortcomings while presenting its achievements.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the speeches of the delegation members often
were applauded by the listeners, which "created a favorable
environment and is very encouraging."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the prospect of resolving the disputes between
different countries on the human rights issue, Zhu quoted an old
saying in the West, "All roads lead to Rome," and said that only
when people agree that various countries should follow their own
ways of improving human rights according to their own situation
can a correct way of resolving the disputes be found.
</P>
<P>
To regard only one point of view on human rights as a defining
creed will not help eliminate disputes, but rather intensify them,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the growing trend of dialogue provides a good prospect
for resolving the disputes on the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
He added that dialogue will finally overcome confrontation and
pave the way for properly resolving the disputes -- even though
the disputes cannot be resolved overnight.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the China Society for Human Rights Studies will more
actively maintain contact and engage in dialogue with both
government and non-government organizations in other countries in
an effort to help increase mutual understanding of human rights.
</P>
<P>
The society will also conduct studies on some fundamental
issues relating to China's human rights policies, such as
judicial, ethnic minority and women's issues -- all areas which
are deeply misunderstood by some other countries, Zhu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Agrees to Meet Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
today agreed to meet Kenya's opposition leaders next week to
discuss the issue of constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here today, opposition leader in
parliament Michael Wamalwa said that Moi held a brief talk with
him this morning and agreed to his request for a meeting between
the Kenyan government and opposition parties next week.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan leader yesterday held talks with 17 religious
leaders on issues relating to constitutional reforms.
</P>
<P>
At yesterday's meeting, both sides agreed that violence must
be condemned and emerging culture of incitement, provocation and
confrontation be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
During the past several weeks, the East African country has
experienced the worst political unrest in recent years as
pro-reform rallies had been organized by opposition parties to
press for constitutional reforms before the coming general
elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
