<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Defense Secretary William S. Cohen will recommend General
Henry H. Shelton of the Army, who commanded the American military
operation in Haiti in 1994, to be the next chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, a senior Administration official said.
</P>
<P>
-- The head of the Russian Space Agency proposed that the
American astronaut Michael Foale participate in a tricky space
walk to repair the stricken Mir space station. The Russian
commander has been judged unable to carry out the job because of
heart irregularities. NASA officials said they needed to be
persuaded of the urgency of the repair before they would allow
Mr. Foale to take on the potentially risky mission.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Clinton resumed budget negotiations Tuesday and
insisted the deficit would not be eliminated without the plan he
is crafting with Congress, despite new reports suggesting the
booming economy may erase the red ink on its own.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- The Veterans Affairs department has begun processing the
first in a potential tidal wave of compensation claims for
smoking-related diseases and deaths. The claims could cost the
government billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Whitewater prosecutor Starr ruled that the 1993 death of
White House aide Vincent Foster was a suicide. Three previous
investigations reached the same conclusion, and Starr's nearly
three-year inquiry proceeded as numerous conspiracy theories
developed. An appeal court is reviewing his report. 
</P>
