<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijackers Returned To Mainland From Taiwan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan handed over two suspected
hijackers to representatives of the Red Cross Society of China
(RCSC) today at Jinmen (Quemoy) in the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The action is in accordance with the Jinmen Agreement signed in
September 1990 between Red Cross organizations across the Straits.
</P>
<P>
The hijackers, Huang Shugang and Han Fengying, together with
accomplices, hijacked a China Southern Airlines plane and a
Sichuan Airlines plane on April 6 and September 30, 1993,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the RCSC, serving as a witness for the
return procedure today, said that hijacking is regarded as a
serious crime everywhere in the world, and hijackers must be
severely punished.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We welcome the Taiwan side's actions of sending back
Huang Shugang and Han Fengying after our side returned the
suspected hijacker, Liu Shan-chung, to Taiwan on May 14."
</P>
<P>
On March 10, Liu Shan-chung hijacked a plane belonging to
Taiwan's Far Eastern Airlines, forcing it to land at Gaoqi Airport
in Fujian Province's Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that Taiwan's departments concerned, for the general
purpose of doing things in favor of jointly combating the crime of
hijacking and safeguarding the lives and property of people across
the Taiwan Straits, will send all suspected hijackers staying in
Taiwan back to mainland areas," the representative said.
</P>
<P>
After being sent back to the mainland, Huang and Han, the two
suspected hijackers, will be prosecuted for their criminal
liability by the judiciary on the mainland according to law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
