<HEADLINE> Malaria Claims 150 lives in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaria has killed about 150
people in east Uganda in the last two months, reported the local
paper, the New Vision, today.
</P>
<P>
Richard Oketch, the district medical officer of Kapchorwa,
said the disease was on the rise in the district.
</P>
<P>
Local sources attributed the high mortality to malnutrition
caused by famine.
</P>
<P>
Kapchorwa is one of the 19 famine-stricken districts in Uganda
in this dry season.
</P>
<P>
Another report from the west said malaria and measles are
spreading in Kasese district.
</P>
<P>
Francis Owori, the superintendent of Kagando hospital in the
district, confirmed his hospital treated 662 cases of measles on
July 8 alone.
</P>
<P>
Most patients are displaced people who fled their homes to
escape harassment from rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said some displaced people are forced to sleep
in the open at night and get malaria from mosquitoes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
