<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expert Calls for Dialogue on Human Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese leading human rights
expert stressed here today that the divergent opinions on human
rights issues should be settled through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Muzhi, president of the China Society for Human Rights
Studies (CSHRS), said during an interview that active and
extensive dialogue should be conducted among different countries
in a bid to deepen mutual understanding, eliminate
misunderstandings, reduce differences, strengthen cooperation and
finally to promote human rights.
</P>
<P>
Zhu and the human rights studies delegation he led have
returned from a visit to Norway, Sweden, Italy and Spain. During
the June 8-27 visit, the delegation met with the respective
governments, parliaments, non-governmental organizations and
people from all trades. It also met with representatives of
Amnesty International in Norway.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that a Chinese non-governmental human
rights group has held discussions with foreign countries on the
specific issue of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that China has made much progress in the area of human
rights, and facts will show that China's attitude toward this
issue has won sympathy and support from many countries, especially
the developing countries and insightful personages from the West.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China strongly opposes confrontation on the
human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
China has maintained a sound relationship with the above four
countries, Zhu said. However, due to lack of contact and
exchanges, differences of opinion remain between the two sides
regarding human rights.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the extensive contacts carried out this time have
helped to make each side's viewpoints known and deepen mutual
understanding, and his views were well received by all four
countries.
</P>
<P>
This will benefit not only the mutual understanding of the
human rights issue, but also the nation-to-nation friendly
relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu, the crowning achievement of this visit is
that dialogue has been initiated, thus the road for further talks
has been broadened and confidence strengthened.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegation exchanged views and discussed
many important issues concerning China's human rights with their
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Several questions were discussed:
</P>
<P>
-- How should the human rights condition in China be evaluated?
</P>
<P>
-- Is it or is it not a noteworthy achievement for China to be
able to feed and clothe 22 percent of the world's population with
seven percent of the world's arable land, and to give its 1.2
billion Chinese people their right to life and development?
</P>
<P>
-- How should China's democracy be evaluated?
</P>
<P>
-- Does China have a developing economy and a non-democratic
political life, or is it economic development that meets the
Chinese people's desire for a better life and a prosperous
country, and thus best reflects the democracy?
</P>
<P>
-- Has the rapid economic progress proved that the People's
Congress system is a democratic one that conforms with the
specific situation of China and ensures the government operates at
the will of the people?
</P>
<P>
-- How should China's rapid economic growth be evaluated?
</P>
<P>
-- Is it beneficial for a prosperous China to provide a big
market and enormous job opportunities to the world, and to develop
its friendly relationship with all countries, or is it beneficial
for a weak and disintegrating China to become the source of
millions of refugees?
</P>
<P>
All these questions are crucial for a correct understanding of
China's human rights situation, Zhu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 12:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Plane Crashes in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A military plane crashed today in
western Turkey, injuring three officers, the semi-official
Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the plane hit a hill at Dilek Yarimadasi
National Park in Kusadasi town of Aydin province when it was
making a training flight, leaving two military officers and one
non-commissioned officer injured.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Turkish sources as saying that a training plane,
which took off from a training school in Izmir, crashed at noon.
</P>
