<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IPR Violators Penalized by Courts in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to show its strong
stand against violations of intellectual property rights, China's
Supreme People's Court (SPC) made public today five of the
country's court rulings on disputes concerning piracy, trademarks
and other related issues.
</P>
<P>
Two of the cases were won by foreign companies against Chinese
litigants.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Guoguang, SPC vice-president, courts nationwide
have handled 5,296 first-instance trials relating to intellectual
proper in the past 17 months, about 10 percent of which involved
overseas people.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese courts not only protect the intellectual property
rights owned by Chinese citizens in accordance with law, they
also, by referring to international treaties China has ratified,
provide equal safeguards for rights owned by overseas people,"
said Li in a press conference held here today.
</P>
<P>
One of the cases involved the unauthorized production of laser
discs on 19 American blockbuster films, including "Commando," "Die
Hard" and "Top Gun," by two Beijing companies, which did not
receive permission from the producers including the 20th Century
Fox Film Corporation and Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
The No. 1 Beijing Intermediate People's Court ruled at the end
of last year that the two Beijing companies must reimburse the US
movie producers with more than 290,000 yuan (around 34,900 US
dollars), and immediately put a halt to the sales of the pirated
discs. Their pirated discs in stock were also confiscated by the
court.
</P>
<P>
Another case concerned a dispute between a company in east
China's city of Nanjing and two foreign toy production and selling
companies, the Interlego AG of Switzerland and the Lego Overseas
A/S of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign companies were compensated with 20,000 US
dollars for infringement upon their rights to patent, trademarks
and copyrights. The manufacturing facilities of the Baogao
International INC in Nanjing which were used for the illegal
activities have been destroyed under the supervision of the local
court.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the company has been ordered to publish a letter
of apology in a newspaper to the foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Three internal cases involved the theft of geological
prospectors results in Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, the
illegal editing and printing of "The Besieged City," a popular
novel by Qian Zhongshu, and the illegal use of a trademark owned
by a Beijing company by Shanghai businesses.
</P>
<P>
In addition to paying compensation for loss, violators have
also received civil punishments according to law, the senior judge
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
