<HEADLINE> Bargain Hunters Drive Australian Stocks to Firmer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A bullish overnight lead from
Wall Street enticed investors back to the Australian share market
today, with bargain hunters driving the local bourse to a
moderately higher close.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 8.8 points firmer
at 2646.4, ending the slide of the past two days that sliced the
value of key cyclical sectors such as building materials by more
than five percent.
</P>
<P>
Broker Brett O'Donovan said, "today was a settling down day,"
as investors came back into the market after several lower closes.
</P>
<P>
"We followed Wall Street's lead and there wasn't a great deal
of movement," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past couple of days the market has been well down
because investors have been disappointed we are not getting a rate
cut," other brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The share prices firmed with the release of the Westpac Bank
consumer sentiment index which showed a 1.1 point increase.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 240.8 million shares traded worth
521.61 million Australian dollars (383.38 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 15.4 points higher at 4220.4,
while the resources added 3.5 points to 1424.3.
</P>
<P>
Banks were mixed with three of the "big four" closing in
positive territory.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank rose 17 cents, Westpac Bank lifted 13 cents,
ANZ Bank was 3.1 cents higher, and only NBA closed lower by 4.8
cents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
