<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Slides as Rate Concerns Persist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar continued
its slide today to close lower against the greenback, with
speculation over a cut to official interest rates weighing heavily
on the domestic currency.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended at 73.25 U.S. cents compared with
Tuesday's finish of 73.57.
</P>
<P>
ANZ Bank's head of foreign exchange sales, John Reedyk, said
that the currency was looking weaker, and on a technical basis
there was strong support for the unit at 73.15 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Reedyk said the Australian dollar had moved a little higher
this afternoon after Prime Minister John Howard's comments that he
had not been calling for a reduction in interest rates recently.
</P>
<P>
Howard told reporters in Newcastle that he did not speculate on
the direction of interest rates, he had not done so in the past
and would not be doing so today.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the currency was being weighed down by speculation
that the Reserve Bank of Australia could cut the 5.5 percent cash
rate by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar was at 84.55 from
84.05 against the Japanese yen and at 1.3118 from 1.3168 against
the German mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
