<HEADLINE> Britain May Use Proportional Representation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is likely to give the go-ahead for the Proportional Representation
voting system to be introduced for elections to the European
parliament in 1999.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first time voters in mainland Britain have been
able to use the Proportional Represenation, instead of the
first-past-the-post voting system, in a national election, local
press reports said.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair reportedly made it clear that his doubts remain
about using Proportional Represenation for the country's general
elections and there is no prospect of change in the current voting
system in the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
Although details of the new voting system have to be worked
out, there is likely to be a regional lists of candidates who
would be elected by taking advantage of the new system.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that final touches would be made at Thursday's
Cabinet meeting before a formal announcement will be made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
