<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Vows to Restore Kabbah at All Costs, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government, with its
troops in Sierra Leone as part of the west African peacekeeping
force (ECOMOG), has vowed to give all it takes to restore ousted
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah to power, the Nigerian Tribune
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"It is obvious that Nigeria will be abdicating its sense of
mission and responsibility as a sub-regional power, if it holds
its arms and watches helplessly and unconcerned its geo-political
environment being threatened by destructive interests," said
presidency sources on Tuesday, quoted by the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Nigeria is in Sierra Leone in
fulfillment of its bilateral pact with that country and as part
of the sub-region's efforts to restore the elected government.
</P>
<P>
"From Momoh to Tejan Kabbah, those variously in power in
Sierra Leone have solicited Nigerian security assistance,
culminating in a security/defence pact between both countries,"
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The pact was in the process of being strengthened in order to
stabilize the democratically elected government of Kabbah when he
was ousted in the coup on May 25, they said.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria also intervened in Sierra Leone at the instance of
some (unnamed) foreign countries to protect their citizens
trapped in Sierra Leone in the wake of the coup.
</P>
<P>
The sources disclosed that Nigeria's intervention in Liberia
and Sierra Leone was consistent with the principle of its foreign
policy and in consonance with the protection and safeguarding of
its geo-political environment, which is a component of its
national interest.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Sani Abacha said recently that
his government would do all within its powers to ensure that the
nation continues with its leadership role in the continent and
that the country's primary concern was peace and stability in the
sub-region, without which no meaningful development could take
place.
</P>
<P>
The coup in Sierra Leone has received wide condemnation around
the world and west African leaders have since engaged in
persuading the military junta to step down.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) has
decided to place economic embargo on Sierra Leone. If it fails,
the use of force will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Four on Sierra Leone is expea a cted to
hold a meeting tomorrow in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, for a solution
to the crisis in Sierra Leone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
