<HEADLINE> Juvenile Delinquency Declines in Singapore: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Juvenile delinquency declined
this year with fewer juveniles arrested compared to last year,
local television reported today, citing latest statistics from the
Inter-Ministry Committee on Juvenile Delinquency.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that some 980 juveniles were arrested in
the first six months of last year, while this year, the number has
fallen by 6 percent to 925 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of juveniles involved in rioting or
fighting remained "unacceptably high", the committee report said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Law and Home Affairs Ho Peng Kee said
that prevention and rehabilitation are the two broad thrusts of
the committee's approach to tackle the problem.
</P>
<P>
The measures include preventive education, age restriction on
entry to entertainment outlets, and Honorary Volunteer Special
Constabulary (VSC) scheme. The first batch of 11 Honorary VSC
senior officers, who are teachers with police powers, was
appointed today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
