<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait's State Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's state reserves have
registered an increase of 21 percent during the past four years to
reach 17 billion dinars (56.1 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of
last may.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Finance Minister Nasser Al-Roudhan attributed the
increase to the improved gain of returns for the Kuwaiti Reserve
Fund for Future Generations and the State Public Reserve which
recorded 11.7 billion U.S. dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
He was responding grillings by parliamentary members over his
ministry's alleged mismanagement of public funds during a
marathon debate at the National Assembly late last night.
</P>
<P>
The minister said growth rate of the returns on the two
reserves were around 15 percent on average during these years.
</P>
<P>
He also declared that returns on the state investments in the
1996/97 fiscal year ending on June 30 even surpassed oil revenues
realized during 1995/96 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Oil revenues in 1995/96 in the oil-rich Gulf state were over 3
billion Kuwait dinars or about 10 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti Reserve Fund for Future Generations used to have a
reserve of more than 100 billion U.S. dollars before the Gulf
War. Since then, the government has been reportedly taking 80
billion U.S. dollars from the reserve to meet the budget deficit
resulted from the war cost and the post-war rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's financial reputation dramatically improved and its
credit rating increased from 38.9 percent to 45.2 percent,
Al-Roudhan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
