<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS FMs to Meet on Sierra Leone Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) are expected to meet
tomorrow in Abidjan, capital of Cote d'Ivoire, to discuss
solutions to the crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say that the meeting is likely to break new
grounds for the sub-regional body to achieve a peaceful
resolution of the crisis, local newspaper This Day reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigeria's Defence Headquarters said on Tuesday the
sub-regional peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG had not got
orders from ECOWAS to take military action against coup leaders
in that country.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG troops were sent to Sierra Leone in the wake of the May
25 coup in a bid to restore the toppled civilian government led
by President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Fightings have been reported between ECOMOG troops and
soldiers loyal to coup leader Major Johnny Koroma, but Nigeria's
acting defence spokesman, Col. Godwin Ugbo, said ECOMOG merely
defended its positions when they were attacked.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping force would maintain its defensive positions
until a contrary directive from ECOWAS high command was received,
Ugbo added.
</P>
<P>
The last clash broke out last weekend when soldiers of Sierra
Leone's military government and ex-rebels of the Revolutionary
United Front attempted to enter ECOMOG-controlled Lungi
internatioinal airport near the capital Freetown, in search of a
radio station alleged to be launched for anti-government
propaganda.
</P>
<P>
About 100 persons were reportedly dead during the fighting,
but Ugbo said on Tuesday the figure was exaggerated to undermine
the efforts by ECOWAS for restoring ousted President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
It is noted this is the first time the Nigerian military
admitted casualties in Sierra Leone though Ugbo declined to
provide the actual figure.
</P>
<P>
According to him, ECOMOG will start economic blockade on
Sierra Leone next week following the action plan by the ECOWAS
Committee of Four on that country.
</P>
<P>
The sub-region will not embark on the use of force to oust the
Koroma-led military government until it is convinced that
economic embargo option has failed, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that tomorrow's Abidjan meeting is likely to be
a forum for working out a truce because Ghana, one of the
Committee of Four, has said it will not support the use of force
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The other memebers of the Committee are Nigeria, Guinea and
Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The people in Cote d'Ivoire are also said to have close
relations with the young hot-heads that sacked Kabbah's
government, which would make them reluctant to take a hardline
against them.
</P>
<P>
The military government in Sierra Leone has consistently
rebuffed appeals by regional leaders and the international
community to quit government and restore President Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Koroma sworn in 12 ministers of the 17-member
cabinet appointed by him last week. The other five will soon take
oath of office.
</P>
<P>
Koroma has said his government will leave but only after
organizing election and installing another government.
</P>
<P>
No timetable has been announced although the military junta
was reported to ask for a period of 18 months to step down
shortly after the coup.  
</P>
</TEXT>
