<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Industrial Zones in Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's Thanlyin-Kyauktan
Industrial Zone, situated 50 kilometers from Yangon, the capital
of the country, is making progress with investment from Singapore
and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Of the 17 container wharves to be set up at the Thilawa Port in
the 1,230-hectare industrial zone, 10 are being built by three
Singaporean companies and four others undertaken by a Malaysian
company.
</P>
<P>
The remaining three wharves are to be built by the Italian-Thai
Development Public Co. Ltd. of Thailand under an agreement with
the Myanmar Port Authority, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
Of the Singaporean investment, the first 500-meter container
wharf, built by the C and P Holding Pte Ltd. of Singapore, has
been completed and put into service, and the second 500-meter
wharf, being built by the same company, is scheduled for
completion at the end of this year with a total handling capacity
of 500,000 containers per year.
</P>
<P>
Another Singaporean company -- the Myanmar Integrated Port
services -- has also completed a wharf there.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Mitsui Company is building another industrial zone at
the Mingaladon area, about 18 kilometers from Yangon, utilizing 89
hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some other industrial zones in Yangon for local
entrepreneurs at Hlaingtharya, Shwepyithar and Dagon Myothit are
also being set up to boost domestic products and exports and
generate more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Of these, the Hlaingtharya Industrial Zone is regarded as the
most successful one with over 50 factories already set up by
local investors engaged in the food processing, textile,
engineering, electrical goods, chemical, forest products and
animal feed industries.
</P>
<P>
Multinational companies are also joining in the development of
the zone leasing land from the Myanmar Housing Development
Authorities and setting up factories making dairy products,
galvanized iron sheet and sanitary products.
</P>
<P>
In addition to those around the capital, industrial zones are
also planned in other parts of Myanmar, including Mandalay, Bago,
Myaungmya, Hinthada, Myeik, Yenangyaung and Pyay.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Myanmar plans to establish 17
industrial zones in the country.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics show that the country's growth
rate of the industrial sector was registered at 5.2 percent in
1996-97 fiscal year ending March and is targeted at 10 percent in
the next fiscal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
