<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's IPR Disputes Up: Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese courts nationwide have
handled 5,296 intellectual property rights (IPR) disputes in the
past 17 months and concluded 4,735 cases during the same period, a
senior judge said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lawsuits involving IPR disputes are on the rise, and the number
of disputes on rights violations is climbing, said Li Guoguang,
vice-president of the Supreme People's Court (SPC), at a press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of court battles over IPR
violations in 1996 was 11.8 percent higher than in 1995, and the
figure for the first five months this year had rocketed by 15.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The rising rate of litigation indicates that, on the one hand,
the IPR owners are more and more aware of the role of law and are
taking up legal means for the protection of their interests. On
the other hand, quite a small number of businesses are still
illegally exploiting other people's labor for their own profit,"
Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li claimed that Chinese courts' timely crackdowns on piracy and
other IPR violations have protected the legitimate rights of both
domestic and foreign owners of intellectual properties, and played
an important role in maintaining the country's economic order and
cultural markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the senior judge, such disagreements usually occur
in prosperous areas: In Beijing, Shanghai, Jiangsu and Guangdong
alone, IPR cases handled by local courts account for one fourth of
the total in the country.
</P>
<P>
And a variety of unexpected cases are emerging, ranging from
stealing geological prospecting results to theft of computer
software rights, Li said. And because rights violations are
sometimes intertwined with disputes on rights ownership and
contracts, it is sometimes difficult for a judge to make a ruling,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Also, the fact that these cases always involve hi-tech matters
and large sums of money causes even more headaches for judges.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president said that to improve the legal system for
IPR protection, the Supreme People's Court has set up a special
IPR Court Office, and local courts now have similar organizations
and their own specialized personnel.
</P>
<P>
"Providing a sufficient judicial guarantee for IPR is a
long-term heavy task for the Chinese courts," Li admitted,
pledging that the Chinese courts will continue their tough stance
against IPR violations in the years to come. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
