<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Meets Israeli Opposition Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held a meeting today with visiting Israeli Labor Party leader Ehud
Barak on the stalled Mideast peace process, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak, on the second day of his two-day visit, will discuss
with Egyptian officials on the efforts to salvage the peace
process which came to a halt after Israel planned and broke ground
for the construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa held talks with the Israeli
opposition leader on Tuesday evening, which he later described as
"favorable and constructive."
</P>
<P>
He called on Israel to halt the settlement project which has
triggered waves of Arab unrest in the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
"It is important to halt all practices that frustrate the
Palestinians and open the way to violence," Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Moussa, Barak expressed appreciation for
Egypt's effective role in the Mideast peace process and urged all
parties to work for resuming peace negotiations in a bid to stop
violence.
</P>
<P>
He added that stopping violence needs some effort by
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat, with whom
he had a telephone conversation Tuesday on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Both U.S. and Egyptian mediation efforts have so far failed to
get the two sides back to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Party decided two months ago to recognize the
Palestinians' right to self-determination and leave open the
possibility of establishing a Palestinian state, which has been
adamantly rejected by Israel's Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who was elected on June 4 to succeed former Labor Party
leader Shimon Peres, is widely regarded as the only person that
could pose a strong challenge to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Now the Labor is working to mobilize Israeli public opinion for
an early election which many hope will bring it back to power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
