<HEADLINE> Austria Pledges to Back Palestinians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima
said today that Austria supports Palestinians' efforts to push
further the Middle East peace process and would vote against
Israel in the United Nations and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat today, Klima
told reporters that Austria condemned Israel for building Jewish
settlements in the Palestinian occupied territories and supported
a Palestinian resolution calling for the United Nations sanctions
upon Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said he had assured Arafat that Austria would do its utmost
to help restart the Middle East peace negotiations, which broke up
in March when Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu ordered
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Klima said the international community should provide economic
aid and favorable investments needed by the Palestinians, who are
suffering an unbearable unemployment rate of 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the 90-minute talks, Klima and Arafat discussed
cooperation in irrigation, education, health care and
infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who is in his first day of a two-day visit to Austria,
called for European intervention in the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are facing some troubles and I am looking to (Viktor
Klima), to Europe, to the international community to protect the
peace process. We are in need of help," Arafat said after meeting
Klima.
</P>
<P>
"The European Union should more and more push its role in the
peace process. We have reached a stalemate."
</P>
<P>
Before the trip to Vienna, Arafat had met British Prime
Minister Tony Blair in London, asking the European countries to
exert pressure on Israel by imposing economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Austria will both hold the European Union's
six-month rotating presidency next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
