<HEADLINE> Brutal Killer's Identity Confused in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The killer of 11 women in Tehran
has been officially identified as an Iranian man instead of
previously-described Afghan, giving a relief to the Afghan
community terribly fearful of a retaliation.
</P>
<P>
The confirmation by Iranian Interior Minister Ali Mohammed
Besharati came amid allegations by the Iranian press that the man,
identified by the Iranian police as Abdullah Abdurrahman, was from
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"The man is from Qouchan city, Khorassan province, northeastern
Iran. His name is Gholamreza Khoshrouy Kouran Kordiyeh," Besharati
was quoted in Persian daily Akhbar today.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister said that the murderer had been
introduced as an Afghan because he gave conflicting accounts about
his identity.
</P>
<P>
Kordiyeh was arrested in Tehran two weeks ago and charged with
killing 11 Iranian women.
</P>
<P>
Posing as a night-time cab driver, Kordiyeh would drive his
female victims outside of the city. After raping and stabbing
them, he would burn their corpses, in an attempt to destroy the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian police has come under fire from the public for
issuing delayed warning to citizens of Kordiyeh's murders.
</P>
<P>
Since the publication of the murder story in the past two
weeks, the Afghan community in the country has lived under
constant fear of being retaliated for the murder blame.
</P>
<P>
The editorial published by Akhbar last week said that murders
and rapes by a group of Afghan criminals are an unfair way of
responding to what the paper called the gracious reception
offered by Iran.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest figures issued by the Interior
Ministry, 1.28 million Afghans live in Iran. They have provided a
constant supply of cheap labor in fields like construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
