<HEADLINE> One Injured in Parcel Bomb Blast at Japan's TV Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A parcel bomb exploded at the
headquarters of Nippon Television Network Corp. here around noon
today, injuring one person, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The parcel, addressed to Yumi Ida, one of Japan's most popular
female newscasters, exploded at about 12:05 on the third floor of
the building in Tokyo's Chiyoda Ward.
</P>
<P>
The explosion occurred when Masamichi Maeda, manager of the TV
company's department of services to viewers, tried to open the
envelope, which contained what appeared to be a video-cassette
tape, police said.
</P>
<P>
The blast left Maeda with wounds to his head and thumb.
</P>
<P>
The parcel, which reached the company Monday, had been sent to
the department handling services to viewers because the newscaster
claimed she had no idea of the sender of the parcel.
</P>
<P>
Police said they have launched an investigation into the case
on the basis of bodily injury and attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
In December 1994, a parcel sent to a popular child actress,
exploded at the TV station, leaving three people wounded. No
arrests have been made regarding that case.  
</P>
</TEXT>
