<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Funds To Help Protect China's Wetlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The UN sponsored Global
Environmental Facility (GEF) today started a project to help
protect China's wetlands, to which GEF will donate 18 million US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Wetlands are an important ecological system and regarded by
experts as the "kidney of the earth." Wetlands not only play a
crucial role in adjusting climate and controlling flood, but also
are home to many waterbirds and have rich bio-diversity resources.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhibao, vice-minister of forestry, today told a press
conference that the GEF's donation will be spent to better protect
several experimental nature reserves for wetlands in China.
</P>
<P>
These reserves include Xingkai Lake and Sanjiang Plain in
Heilongjiang Province, Yancheng in Jiangsu Province, Ruoergai in
both Sichuan and Gansu provinces, and East Dongting Lake in Hunan
province.
</P>
<P>
According to experts, these reserves for wetlands are all of
international importance.
</P>
<P>
China has some of the richest wetlands resources in the world,
the total area of which reaches 63 million hectares.
</P>
<P>
"So far, 152 natural reserves for wetlands have been
established in China," said the vice-minister, adding that the
protection of wetlands has been listed as one of the priorities on
China's 21st century agenda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Takes India to WTO over Trade Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia has challenged India in
the World Trade Organization (WTO) over more than 2700
quantitative trade restrictions applied by India on imports,
Australian Deputy Prime Minister and Minister For Trade Tim
Fischer announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Australia, along with several other countries including the
United States and New Zealand, has formally requested WTO
consultations with India on the issue, Fischer said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"The restrictions are denying Australian exporters fair access
to the Indian market for a whole range of goods including
agricultural commodities, processed foods, precious stones,
automotive components, various electrical and mechanical items,
and textiles," the deputy prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said the restrictions are "a major obstacle, and can no
longer be justified".
</P>
<P>
The Indian restrictions have been in place for about 50 years.
They were intended to provide India with a breathing space to
address balance of payments problems, but have become a permanent
feature of India's trade regime, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
"India no longer has a balance of payments problem... Its
foreign reserves are at record levels and the economy is
responding strongly to recent trade and financial liberalization,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the removal of these restrictions would give a further
boost to the Indian economy, Fischer argued.
</P>
<P>
Under WTO rules, India is required to replace its quantitative
restrictions with tariffs as soon as possible. But India insisted
on a seven-year phase-out period, with many agricultural products
of major interest to Australia not being subject to phase-out
until the very end of this period, he complained.
</P>
<P>
"Australia is prepared to accept a reasonable period for the
phase-out, but seven years is too long, and extensive negotiations
between India and its trading partners in WTO forums have made no
progress on this issue," the deputy prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said Australia would prefer an early resolution to the
issue through consultation, rather than pursuing it further in the
WTO Dispute Settlement Body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
