<HEADLINE> Mandela, Chavalit to Boost Trade, Tourism Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 16 (Xinhua) -- South African President Nelson
Mandela arrived here today on a two-day official visit, during
which trade and tourism will be among the main topics of
discussion between leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A Thai Foreign Ministry source said both sides feel that there
is ample room for the expansion of bilateral trade, which reached
10.39 billion baht (407 million US dollars) last year, with
Thailand incurring a 904 million baht (35.5 million dollar)
deficit.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was attributed to the lack of competitiveness of
Thailand's main exports -- textiles and garments, rice, frozen
chicken and canned seafood.
</P>
<P>
President Mandela and Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
would also discuss tourism cooperation. About 20,000 South African
tourists visited Thailand last year, while only 5,000 Thais
visited South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela and Chavalit will also exchange ideas about how best to
boost two-way investment, which has so far been very small.
</P>
<P>
The Thai side would also hope that business people of the two
countries would join forces to explore infrastructure investment
opportunities in Indochina.
</P>
<P>
The source also said Thailand would seek support from South
Africa for its bid for membership in the 14-member Indian ocean
rim.
</P>
<P>
Mandela will be granted an audience with King Bhumibol
Adulyadej later today and will be conferred on an honorary
doctorate degree of liberal arts at the Chulalongkorn university.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is scheduled to depart Thursday afternoon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
