<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Rebels Warn of Long Deadlock in Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The leader of the rebel Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) today warned of a long deadlock in
its peace talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
Al Haj Murad, MILF vice chairman for military affairs, made the
warning following President Fidel Ramos' statement on Tuesday that
the government would not give in to the rebels' demand for the
pull-out of military troops in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
"We are just being logical and practical," Murad said, adding
the government would have to wait a "proper time" before
re-opening the talks stalled by the military's recent operatives
against the MILF.
</P>
<P>
The MILF set four pre-conditions for the resumption of the
peace talks, including the withdrawal of government troops from
the areas of conflicting in Cotabato and Maguindanao provinces.
</P>
<P>
So far, the government has been positively acting on all the
demands except on the pull-out of troops which the MILF considers
as vital in breaking the impasse.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Murad also vehemently denied allegations that
his guerrillas shelled government troops in Buldon, Maguindanao
province on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that contrary to military reports, his troops did not
fire a single shot from any of their weapons. He added that the
mortars came from the military's position and landed in the MILF's
encampment.
</P>
<P>
"I investigated our mortars and rocket propelled grenades and
they showed no evidence that they have been fired," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Col. Vivencio Bataga, commander of the 39th
Infantry Battalion, accused the rebels of pounding their position
in Buldon with 38 rounds of 60 mm and 81 mm mortars.
</P>
<P>
The attack occurred before the second extension of a unilateral
ceasefire declared by the military which was expiring at 6 a.m.
the same day.
</P>
<P>
It was unknown whether there was casualties in the attack.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a 12,000-member group which had fought government
troops in the southern Philippines. The government has been
pursuing peace talks with it since earlier this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
