<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, July 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Despite Israel's threat to erase a cease-fire which
Lebanon and Israel reached in April 1996, a fresh volley of
Katyusha rockets were fired into the so-called "security zone"
after midnight, with some landing in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the Israeli self-carved buffer zone in
south Lebanon said that some 20 Katyusha rockets were launched
Wednesday at the Israeli positions of Blat and Abbat in the
western sector of the border strip.
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Tourist arrivals in the Philippines rose by 10
percent to 705,800 during the first four months of this year, the
Philippine News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a report from the Department of Tourism as
saying that the bulk of the tourists came from East Asia,
especially from Japan, while the United States was the biggest
market for the Philippines' tourism among the western countries.
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- President Fidel Ramos said that the Philippine
government is trying its best to forge peace pacts with all of the
country's rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
During an unofficial meeting with Colin Powell, former chairman
of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, Ramos said the rift between the
government and the remaining insurgency groups was "really not an
ideological issue but a three-meals-a-day issue."
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's industrial production increased slightly in
the first half of the year but the economic situation remains
critical, according to an economic report released by the State
Statistical committee.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output rose by 0.8 percent, representing an increase
for the first time in six years but the gross domestic product
dropped by 0.2 percent from the same period last year, the highest
drop in six years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The European Commission, the executive organ of the
European Union (EU), agreed on a document on Tuesday which names
five Eastern European nations and Cyprus as prospective new
members of the union.
</P>
<P>
The document, Agenda 2000, paves the way for negotiations to
begin next year on the entry of the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Hungary, Poland, Slovenia and the Mediterranean island of Cyprus
to the 15-member bloc.
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Politicians here welcome Slobodan Milosevic's
election Tuesday as president of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, saying it is an event conducive to the political
stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic contributed to national peace and stability during
its transitional period, said Milutin Stojkovic, chairman of the
parliamentarian group of the ruling Socialist Party of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- Three Sri Lankan soldiers and three Tamil rebels
were killed Tuesday in a clash in Valachenai town in Eastern
Province, according reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The reports said a group of soldiers were on a route clearing
patrol when they were ambushed and attacked by the rebels. A
soldier was also wounded.
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- U.N. peacekeeping forces on Tuesday started to leave
Eastern Slovenia, an area to be reverted to Croatia by mid-January
next year.
</P>
<P>
At the headquarters of the U.N. Transitional Authority in
Eastern Slovenia (UNTAES), a farewell ceremony was held for the
2,400 departing soldiers of the Pakistani and Jordanian battalions
and an Argentine technical unit.
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine will launch Sea Breeze-97 naval exercise with
the United States and other North Atlantic Treaty Organization
navies as scheduled, from August 25 to 31.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian Defense Minister Alexander Kuzmuk said on Tuesday
that the Black Sea exercise aims to provide humanitarian aid after
devastating earthquakes in nearby countries.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain's Queen Elizabeth celebrated her golden
wedding Tuesday in Buckingham Palace with 4,000 couples whose
marriage also lasted for half a century.
</P>
<P>
The queen and her husband Prince Philip invited couples from
the commonwealth countries who married, as they did, in 1947, to a
special Golden Wedding garden party.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government said Tuesday it had not
changed its decision to ban official talks with the IRA's
political wing, Sinn Fein, despite renewed contacts with the
latter.
</P>
<P>
A spokeswoman for the Northern Ireland Office said: "There has
been no change in policy because we have said there would be no
meetings and there have not been any meetings." 
</P>
