<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought-hit Uganda Expects Rains in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The dry season now causing famine
in 19 of total 45 districts in Uganda is expected to end in
mid-September, meteorological department was quoted here today by
local newspaper, The New Vision.
</P>
<P>
A press release signed by Bwango Apuuli, the commissioner for
meteorology, said that the coming rainy season is predicted to be
a long one and is expected to last to the end of this year or
beginning of the next.
</P>
<P>
The coming rainy season is expected to bring heavy rain in the
whole country and should offer an opportunity for a bumper
harvest, the press release reads.
</P>
<P>
This dry season began in most north and east areas in March,
usually the beginning of a two and half months of a rainy season.
The change of the season was caused by El-Nino effect, a
phenomenon reflecting abnormal sea surface warming of the
equatorial Pacific ocean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
