<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatized Zambian Copper Giant Asked to Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 14 (Xinhua) -- Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM) has been stripped of its special status and will from now
on pay taxes promptly like any others, Times of Zambia reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted Zambia Revenue Authority (ZRA)
acting Commissioner General Abraham Geevarghese as saying here
Sunday that in view of the on-going privatization of ZCCM, ZRA
has made it a policy to treat the conglomerate on an equal foot
with any other companies and will demand immediate settlement of
taxes from ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
He said previously ZCCM was given a longer period to pay its
taxes because of the size and nature of the company.
</P>
<P>
"Now with the privatization of ZCCM, we are asking them to pay
both tax and duty promptly like any body else, they will no
longer enjoy any privileges or special treatment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Privatization Agency (ZPA) recently estimated the ZCCM
debt at two billion Kwacha (about 1.5 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
ZCCM earns the country 80 percent of its foreign exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
