<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 08:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Katyusha Attack Launched in S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Despite Israel's threat to erase a
cease-fire which Lebanon and Israel reached in April 1996, a fresh
volley of Katyusha rockets were fired into the so-called "security
zone" after midnight, with some landing in northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Security sources in the Israeli self-carved buffer zone in
south Lebanon said that some 20 Katyusha rockets were launched
Wednesday at the Israeli positions of Blat and Abbat in the
western sector of the border strip.
</P>
<P>
At least five rockets crashed across the border and landed in
northern Israel without causing casualties, the sources said on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
No faction fighting the Jewish state in south Lebanon has
claimed responsibility for the Katyusha attack.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah, or Party of God, which
spearheads a guerrilla warfare against the Israeli occupation in
south Lebanon, fired more than 15 Katyusha rockets into the
border strip Tuesday. One rocket exploded inside Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
Two civilians were wounded when rockets hit Dimashkieh, four
kilometers west of the largest town of Marjayoun in the buffer
zone, the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia claimed.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after two Palestinian civilians residing in
south Lebanon were killed and a third wounded Monday in
bombardment by SLA militia in revenge for an earlier guerrilla
attack on a SLA patrol.
</P>
<P>
Later on Tuesday, the SLA-run Voice of the South radio warned
that civilians would be shelled if the Katyusha salvoes did not
stop, a declaration similar to an erasion of the cease-fire
understanding.
</P>
<P>
"So far, the IDF (Israeli Defense Force) has maintained
self-restraint and not fired directly at villages. But if
Hezbollah continues to breach the (April) understanding ... the
IDF will target civilians as a response for the shelling of
northern Israel," the radio quoted Amiran Levine, commander of
Israel's northern military area, as saying.
</P>
<P>
While the April understanding permits conflict between Israeli
troops, the SLA and resistance guerrilla troops, it rules out
harming both Lebanese and Israeli civilians.
</P>
<P>
Today's pre-dawn Katyusha attack took place several hours
before a meeting of the five-nation panel at the south Lebanon
border town of Naqoura to discuss two complaints filed by the
Lebanese government, the first over the shelling by Israeli
forces Saturday in which a 70-year-old farmer was killed, and
the second over Monday's bloody bombardment.
</P>
<P>
This will be the 14th meeting this year of the cease-fire
monitoring committee which groups representatives from France,
Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which is currently under the chairmanship of
the U.S. representative, normally calls for restraint between the
combatants rather than apportioning blame, leading both Lebanon
and Israel in the past to denounce its ineffectiveness.
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,100-square-kilometer "security zone"
in 1985 ostensibly to protect northern Israel from cross-border
attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
