<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hungary Introduces New Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Hungary will launch a multi-layer
pension system in 1998 to curb the government's rising pension
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
Under a law passed by the parliament today, starting from 1998
workers will have to deposit seven percent of their income in
special pension savings accounts in banks to supplement the
pensions they receive from the government when they retire.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven percent of their income, six percent will go to
their individual pension savings accounts, which are stipulated as
personal property, and one percent to the state pension fund.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, their employers have to contribute an amount
of money equivalent to 24 percent of the payroll to the state
pension fund.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, young people beginning their jobs from July 1,
1998, have to choose the "individual pension savings account." But
current workers could opt for the new system or the existing one
under which the government pays an old-age pension to retirees.
</P>
<P>
The parliament attributed the need for the new law to an
increasing proportion of old people, unemployment and the failure
of the present pension system to satisfy social demands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
