<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Benefit From Africa Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is set to
derive considerable benefit from trade and investment
opportunities from policy reform and the liberalisation of
capital flows in Africa, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that South Africa's export to African
countries, which almost doubled to 3.7 billion US Dollar (USD)
last year from 2 billion USD in 1993, would be boosted further by
the expected higher trade volumes in the southern African region,
said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's 3 billion USD trade surplus with
Africa also provided key support for the current account. Africa
currently accounts for about 15 percent of South Africa's total
exports (including gold).
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that South Africa, along with its partners in
the five-nation Southern Africa Customs Union, sold products
worth 2.8 billion USD to the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries last year, compared with 1995's 2.2
billion USD.
</P>
<P>
SADC countries, meanwhile, concluded sales worth 467 million
USD to South Africa last year, an improvement from 1995's 333
million USD.
</P>
<P>
Peace and pragmatism of policy makers are helping the SADC
region, with the World Bank estimates put that 37 out of 48
sub-Saharan African countries were undergoing substantial
reforms, said the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
