<HEADLINE> Uganda's Fish Farming Recovers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's fish farming industry
has made a modest recovery from a mere 1,000 ponds in 1987 to
about 3,000 ponds today, with the annual fish output hitting 180
tons, worth 60,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the local newspaper The People today, fish
farming sunk to the doldrum in Uganda in the 1970s in wake of
political turmoil after a boom in the 1960s whereby 11,000 ponds
peaked 800-900 tons of fish annually by 1968.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,200 farmers take part in fish farming throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
Their activities are backed by an increase in fish fry
production in breeding centers in some districts of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Populous Province Meets Summer Grain Purchase Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan Province,
the most populous province and a major grain producer in China,
had bought and stored nearly three billion kg of wheat by July 10,
meeting the state quota for purchasing summer grain.
</P>
<P>
This year's summer harvest set a record in the province. To
encourage farmers to grow more grain, the provincial government
decided to buy grain at last year's price, which was 1.52 yuan per
kg, 10 percent higher than the state-set price, and to build more
grain warehouses.
</P>
<P>
The province needed 7.32 billion yuan for summer grain purchase,
and local financial departments and banks worked to raise enough
funding so that they would not give IOUs to farmers selling grain
to the government.
</P>
<P>
Now, the province has begun to buy any amount of grain
from farmers at market prices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
