<HEADLINE> Malaysia Opens Bank in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's TA Enterprises
has opened a bank in Johannesburg with the initial capital of 150
million Rand (33.3 million U.S. dollars), local daily the Citizen
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The launch of the Malaysian bank was a milestone in the
economic and trade relations between South Africa and Malaysia,
Finance Minister Trevor Manuel was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian investment in South Africa had grown rapidly over
the last three years, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia was recently ranked as South Africa's second largest
investor in terms of foreign direct investment, contributing 20.7
percent of an estimated 6.6 billion U.S. dollars since 1994.
</P>
<P>
TA Enterprise made its first move into South Africa's economy
in early 1996 when it acquired a stockbroking firm, known as TA
Securities.
</P>
<P>
TA Bank is South Africa's 11th foreign bank. There are also
seven branches, and 58 representative offices of foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
Manuel described the increasing foreign investment in South
Africa as a vote of confidence in the South African government's
ability to facilitate and protect investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
There has been an upswing in business confidence as a result
of the government being seen to meet its commitments in
relaxation of foreign exchange controls, Manuel added.
</P>
<P>
South Africa announced last month a program to relax foreign
exchange control, allowing individuals to invest up to 44,444
U.S. dollars abroad as of July 1. There has been no sudden
outflow of capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
