<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 07:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Parliament Fails to Approve No-Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The opposition Kuwaiti
parliamentary members (MP) failed to depose Finance Minister
Nasser Abdullah Al-Roudhan after a session of intense questioning
and accusations last night about his alleged negligence and
mismanagement of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti MPs Sami Al-Munayes, Mishari Al-Osaimi and Ahmed
Al-Mulaifi who had initiated a grilling request of Al-Roudhan,
also deputy prime minister, failed to secure the ten signatures
needed to submit a non-confidence motion against the minister.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-one of the 50 deputies voted to close the stormy
debate without any result.
</P>
<P>
Support for a vote of non-confidence by 24 of 46 elected MPs
in the 50-seat National Assembly would have forced Al-Roudhan to
resign.
</P>
<P>
During the 13-hour debate, Al-Roudhan was accused by the MPs
of failing to implement certain laws, negligence in protecting
public funds while he allowed others to use public properties
irrespective of proper returns.
</P>
<P>
Al-Roudhan made replies to ten issues presented in the queries
and said "this is a good opportunity for me to prove that I
entered the cabinet with a clean white robe," apparently
suggesting that he was innocent of the accusations.
</P>
<P>
Questioning Al-Roudhan, the 12th of its kind since the first
Kuwaiti parliament in 1963, is the first one conducted to a
current cabinet minister by the parliament which was elected in
October last year.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh
Sabah Al-Ahmed Al-Jaber Al-Sabah, expressed his thanks to the
lawmakers who supported Al-Roudhan, while saying the grilling was
a constitutional right.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped people would not consider the grilling as a
victory for some persons or a defeat to others.
</P>
<P>
The three MPs who initiated the questioning vowed to continue
their battle with the "thieves of public funds" and warned
against "further embezzlements." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
