<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dustbins Disappearing in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Dustbins in the Chinese capital,
which are usually placed in residential areas, are being gradually
replaced by enclosed garbage collection centers.
</P>
<P>
The city produces an average of 13,000 tons of garbage each
day. Last year, the total amount of garbage exceeded 4.8 million
tons. Beijing is surrounded by 7,000 landfills and more than 500
hectares of farmland have been covered by garbage.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the municipal government made changes to the
traditional method of garbage collection, asking residents to
place their trash in plastic bags, haul the bags to public trash
carts, which are then taken to the collection centers.
</P>
<P>
By last October, the Xicheng District in Beijing had stopped
using the dustbins and set up 80 collection centers, said an
official from the Municipal Sanitation Department.
</P>
<P>
The official added that the Dongcheng and Xuanwu districts and
95 percent of the streets in the suburban areas would get rid of
the dustbins this year.
</P>
<P>
Some districts in Beijing launched a pilot project last October
for collecting different kinds of garbage in different bags.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this new method both promotes recycling of
resources and is pollution-free.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 1,200 tons of paper can be recycled from
the 1,500 tons of waste paper discarded by Beijing residents each
day, while the amount of gasoline refined from plastic products
thrown away each day would be enough for 30,000 cars to run 100
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
However, the municipal government is facing a shortage of funds
for the collection work.
</P>
<P>
Every day, the city must operate more than 3,000 garbage
trucks, and the transport of each truckload from a residential
quarter to a garbage collection center on the outskirts costs 400
yuan on average.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Municipal Sanitation Department advise that
fees should be collected from all the units and residents in
Beijing, including the migrant population, so that the amount of
garbage will be controlled and enough funding will be raised to
develop new methods of trash collection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
