<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Extends Cease-fire With Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
extended an interim cease-fire with the Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) for another seven days to give the rebel group ample
time to return to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
Arnulfo G. Acedera, chief of the Philippine Armed Forces, told
reporters that the cease-fire was extended at the request of
Governor Nur Misuari of the Autonomous Region for Muslim Mindanao
(ARMM), who visited the presidential palace on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to Acedera, Misuari relayed the message that the MILF
was ready to return to the peace talks as long as the cease-fire
will be extended anew.
</P>
<P>
The government declared the unilateral three-day cease-fire
with the MILF on July 9. When it expired, Manila extended the
cease-fire for four more days.
</P>
<P>
Acedera pointed out that the government has extended the
cease-fire for the second time to give the MILF more time to
examine its position in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The MILF suspended its peace talks with the government two
weeks ago after government forces intensified its military
operation against the Muslim rebel group in Central Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The government accused the MILF of kidnapping businessmen and
residents in Central Mindanao and launched the offensive last
month. About 200 government soldiers and rebels were killed in the
month-long fighting.
</P>
<P>
The MILF has become the major rebel group in the Philippines
after the government and Misuari's Moro National Liberation Front
signed an accord on peace in Mindanao last September.
</P>
<P>
The peace agreement was rejected by the MILF, which vowed to
continue its fighting for an independent Muslim state in the
Southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Misuari is now acting as a mediator between the government and
the MILF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
