<HEADLINE> House Approves Block Grants for Preventing Juvenile Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States House of
Representatives Tuesday voted to provide states with block grants
for preventing juvenile crime rather than funding programs.
</P>
<P>
The bill would combine the programs into a single source of
money for the states. The states would also gain broader
flexibility in designing anti-crime initiatives, and catering to
their particular needs.
</P>
<P>
The bill, now advancing to the Senate, appropriates no money.
It merely authorizes creation of the block grant.
</P>
<P>
The House Appropriations Subcommittee responsible for the
Department of Justice voted last week to spend 238 million dollars
on programs to fight juvenile crime.
</P>
<P>
Supporters said the prospective law complemented get-tough
legislation that passed the House in May because it focuses on
preventing crime.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, states could use up to 15 percent of their
block-grant money to renovate or replace juvenile facilities. The
measure also reauthorizes programs to serve runaway and homeless
youth, as well as the National Missing Children Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Begins to Implement Ninth Five-Year Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Nepal today began to implement
the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1997-2002), with poverty alleviation as
its major objective.
</P>
<P>
The ninth plan aims to lower the poverty percentage from 45 to
32.5 and eventually dropping it to 10 in 20 years' time.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the emphasis has been laid on production, food
security, employment, increase in income, supply of fertilizers,
irrigation, rural roads, electricity and technology.
</P>
<P>
And a special Poverty Alleviation Fund of 40 million rupees
(about 700,000 U.S. dollars) will be set up.
</P>
<P>
Poverty alleviation has been one of the main objectives of the
past plans.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the efforts in the last 40 years, more and
more Nepalese are slipping below the poverty line every year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say to achieve the goal of poverty alleviation as set
in the ninth plan, the development strategies, the management and
implementation aspects of these procedures need urgent reforms.
</P>
<P>
They also doubt the feasibility of a 6.5 percent growth rate
envisaged in the ninth plan due to limited resources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
