in greater Sylhet and southern Chittagong and the hill tracts
regions while diarrhea and dysentery broke out in Bandarban hill
district, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The overall flood situation in southeastern regions is steadily
improving due to stoppage of heavy downpour and resultant fall in
the flow of rivers in these districts.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 people already fell victim to the water-borne
diseases, said official sources, adding that 11 medical teams have
been working to check the spread of diarrhea in the area.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, as many as 69 people died
following flash floods in 96 counties of the country's 21
districts which affected nearly 3 million people.
</P>
<P>
The flood brought on mostly by incessant rainfall for several
days has damaged crops on 160,000 acres of land and about 377,000
dwelling houses, said an official handout.
</P>
<P>
A total of 178 kilometers of embankment had been damaged by
flash floods and 280 bridges and culverts destroyed. Some 286
educational institutions had been totally or partially damaged in
the flood-ravaged districts, the handout said.
</P>
<P>
However, a bulletin of the Flood Information Center said five
rivers in the Brahmaputra, the Ganges and the Meghna basins were
still flowing above their respective danger levels on Tuesday. It
also forecast that more areas of eastern Munshiganj district might
be submerged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
