<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guatemalans Unhappy With Government's Impotence on Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Crime and violence have become
the worst problems in Guatemala and more than half the citizens
are dissatisfied with the government's efforts to fight crime, a
survey shows.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of those surveyed said violence was the
country's No.1 problem, the CID-Gallup survey said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,202 citizens interviewed throughout the country, 54
percent said President Alvaro Arzu's government had done "little
or nothing" to resolve the problem of crime.
</P>
<P>
Figures from humanitarian organizations show there is an
average of 8-10 assassinations in Guatemala every day, while there
is one person kidnapped every 40 hours.
</P>
<P>
As for combating violence, the poll showed that 24 percent of
the citizens believed that Arzu's administration, which began in
January 1996, "has done nothing", and only eight percent believed
"it has done a lot."
</P>
<P>
Other problems facing the community were corruption, the high
cost of living, and unemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
