<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in L.America Triples </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investments in
Latin America and the Caribbean tripled between 1990 and 1995, a
United Nations report said today.
</P>
<P>
Net investments in the region climbed from 8.06 billion
U.S. dollars in 1990 to 23.6 billion dollars in 1995, the
U.N. Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean said
in its 1996 report.
</P>
<P>
The 1995 figure was down from 26 billion dollars in the booming
year of 1994, but was nine billion dollars more than the average
capital inflow between 1991 and 1993 of 14.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Mexico, the favorite of foreign investors, received 31 percent
of the region's total foreign investment in 1995, followed by
Brazil with 21 percent and Argentina with 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the 91-95 period, the geographical distribution of
investment worldwide changed remarkably, with capital increasingly
flowing into developing countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries received 31.8 billion dollars in 1990, or
16 percent of the world's total foreign investment. The figure
rose to 88.8 billion dollars in 1994, or 41 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures showed that overseas investment in
developing countries reached 108.7 billion dollars in 1995,
representing 35 percent of the world's total. Asia attracted the
bulk of it, 65 billion dollars, followed by the Latin America and
the Caribbean which received 23.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. expert said today that the region got an estimated 30
billion dollars investment in 1996, was expected to get between
35-37 billion dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
