<HEADLINE> Family Counselors For Sri Lankan Workers In Mid-East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka Foreign Employment
Bureau (SLFEB) is to appoint family counselors to look into the
welfare of families whose women members are working in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
According to SLFEB sources today, the counselors will visit the
homes of women working in the Middle East and inquire into their
problems.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 80 percent of over 500,000 Sri Lankans working in the
Middle East are women and they make a significant contribution to
the country's economy by remitting millions of dollars per year.
</P>
<P>
The most common problems faced by these families include the
breaking up of their marriages due to the husband's infidelity
during the wife's absence and the spending sprees by husbands
spend money extravagantly. In some cases, their children end up
becoming destitute, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Retired teachers, principals and others with similar standing
in society will be recruited as counselors and will be paid for
the hours they work for the Bureau.  
</P>
</TEXT>
