<HEADLINE> European Commission Considers New EU Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
executive organ of the European Union (EU), agreed on a document
on Tuesday which names five Eastern European nations and Cyprus as
prospective new members of the union.
</P>
<P>
The document, Agenda 2000, paves the way for negotiations to
begin next year on the entry of the Czech Republic, Estonia,
Hungary, Poland, Slovenia and the Mediterranean island of Cyprus
to the 15-member bloc.
</P>
<P>
The prospective candidates, however, are unlikely to get their
membership until at least 2002.
</P>
