<HEADLINE> Southwest City an Emerging Tourist Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Bose, an important historic city
known for its natural beauty and rich folklore, is expected to
become a popular tourist destination with the completion of a
major railway trunk line.
</P>
<P>
Located at the banks of the scenic Chengpi Lake, Bose, in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, is home to
various ethnic minority groups such as the Zhuang, Yao, Miao and
Yi. The city is best-known as a site of a Red Army uprising led by
Deng Xiaoping in December, 1929.
</P>
<P>
The Nanning-Kunming Railway, which runs between the capital of
Guangxi and capital of neighboring Yunnan, is now in trial
operation. Officials not only expect it to bring more tourists to
Bose, but also link the prefecture with other major attractions
elsewhere in Guangxi, and in Yunnan and Guizhou, according to Xie
Xueming, deputy director of Bose prefecture Tourism Bureau.
</P>
<P>
To cater to the upcoming tourist boom, several trans-regional
routes have been worked out, featuring such attractions as the
Bose Uprising Ruins, local ethnic folklore, visits to major
industrial projects, Huangguoshu Waterfall in Guizhou, and Stone
Forest in Yunnan, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Tourists are urged to visit Bose during the colorful festivals
held by local ethnic groups, such as the slope-jumping festival of
the Miao people, the bow-jumping and torch festivals of the Yi
people, and horse-racing and tree-worshiping festivals of the
Gelao minority, Xie noted.
</P>
<P>
Bose has also spruced up its infrastructure with a number of
newly-built hotels, and to offer IDD and international mobile
phone services.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
