<HEADLINE> Primakov Announces Agenda for New York Ministerial Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov today announced the agenda for the Russia-NATO
ministerial meeting scheduled for September in New York.
</P>
<P>
Primakov made the announcement at a joint press conference here
after talking with his German counterpart, Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministerial meeting was to address issues such as
the Bosnian situation, peacekeeping mission, international fight
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It would also explore the possibility of setting up a force
made up of both Russian and NATO troops, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-NATO partnership council, set up under a landmark
pact signed in May giving Moscow a say in some of NATO's affairs,
is to hold its first ministerial meeting in New York alongside the
United Nations' General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Last week NATO's Madrid summit decided to invite the Czech
Republic, Hungary and Poland to join the military alliance,
sparking bitter criticism from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Primakov denounced the expansion plan as the alliance's
"biggest mistake" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Before Kinkel's visit, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook flew to Moscow
to try to massage bruised relations with Russia. The coming
ministerial meeting in New York is another chance for them to
coordinate their relations. 
</P>
