<HEADLINE> Xinjiang to Build Largest Wind Power Base in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region has put the finishing touches on an ambitious
plan to build the largest wind power generating base in Asia,
according to the latest edition of the Beijing-based China
Economic Herald.
</P>
<P>
The recent unification of the Dabancheng No.1 Wind Power Plant,
the Dabancheng No.2 Wind Power Plant in Urumqi, the region's
capital, and the Tuohongtai Wind Power Plant in Buerjin County,
has turned Xinjiang into the largest wind power base in China,
with more than 25,000 kw of installed capacity, accounting for 44
percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
The region will install another 66 wind power generators at the
Dabancheng No.2 Wind Power Plant, some 80 km away from Urumqi, to
have a total installed capacity of 70,000 kw -- the largest in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is rich in wind energy and has nine strong wind areas
with 800 billion kwh of wind resources. In 1989, the region
established the Dabancheng No.1 Wind Power Plant, using donations
from the Denmark government to purchase equipment, and under an
aid project by the German government.
</P>
<P>
The No.1 plant has 22 generators with an installed capacity of
6,100 kw. The No. 2 plant was built there later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
