<HEADLINE> Myanmar Invites More Foreign Bids for Mining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's Ministry of Mines has
announced 12 more new areas in its third round of competitive
bidding, inviting foreign companies to conduct mineral prospecting
and exploration operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The official New Light of Myanmar newspaper today quoted
Tuesday's  announcement by the Ministry as saying that the
"blocks" where foreign firms are permitted to operate include
Kyaungle-Mansi, Namma-Kangon, katha-Indaw, Namhsan and Nammilaung,
each covering an area of 1,400 square km.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has sponsored two rounds of competitive bidding for the
purpose, in which 14 "blocks" were granted to six foreign
companies in the first round in November 1994 and nine "blocks" to
five firms in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
Minerals to be exploited include copper, gold, lead, zinc,
silver, nickel, iron ore, steel and coal.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, 15 foreign companies from five
countries -- Australia, Canada, Singapore, Thailand and the United
States -- have been involved in the mineral exploration in
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The latest official statistics also show that foreign
investment in the mining sector amounted to 498 million U.S.
dollars in 42 permitted projects at the end of May this year.
</P>
