<HEADLINE> Election of Milosevic Conducive to Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Politicians here welcome Slobodan
Milosevic's election Tuesday as president of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia, saying it is an event conducive to the political
stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic contributed to national peace and stability during
its transitional period, said Milutin Stojkovic, chairman of the
parliamentarian group of the ruling Socialist Party of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
And therefore his election is of great historical and political
significance to the whole country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Zeljko Sturanovic, chairman of the parliamentarian group of the
ruling Socialist Democratic Party of the Republic of Montenegro,
said Milosevic's election is conducive to the stability of the
federal republic, and to enhancing the alliance of the ruling
parties of Serbia and Montenegro, the two republics that form the
federal republic.
</P>
<P>
Agreeing with them, Momcilo Perisic, chief of general staff of
the Yugoslav army, noted that the election shows the political
will of citizens of the federal republic to live in a stable
country.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, member of the presidency of the Republic of
Bosnia-Hezergovina Momcilo Krajisnik congratulated Milosevic on
his election, believing his presidency would help stabilize the
political situation in Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, president of Serbia, was elected president of
Yugoslavia by both chambers of the federal parliament to replace
incumbent President Zoran Lilic, and will formally take office on
July 23 for a four-year term.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic, born in Serbia in August 1941, was elected president
of the Serbia Republic in 1989 and again in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
