<HEADLINE> Myanmar Denies Change of Monetary System After ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt has denied that his country would change its monetary
system after becoming a member of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN).
</P>
<P>
Rumors have been circulating here that Foreign Exchange
Certificate (FEC), which is equivalent to the U.S. dollar in value
and widely circulated on the Myanmar market, would be withdrawn
and foreign exchange deposited in the banks by people be seized by
the government after Myanmar's entry into ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is scheduled to be admitted into ASEAN later this month
at the regional grouping's annual ministerial meeting in Kuala
Lumpur according to a decision made at a special meeting of ASEAN
foreign ministers on May 31.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here Tuesday of Myanmar's Leading
Committee for ASEAN Affairs, Khin Nyunt, who is first secretary of
the ruling State Law and Order Restoration Council and chairman of
the committee, urged the public not to believe the rumors spread
by a group of "unscrupulous elements."
</P>
<P>
He said the rumors about the financial and economic matters
afloat among the Myanmar people currently are totally untrue, the
official newspaper the New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
FEC was introduced in Myanmar in 1993 for the convenience of
foreigners visiting and doing business in the country since hard
currency is not allowed for circulation domestically.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar authorities have already denied that the country's
200- and 500-Kyat bank notes would also be withdrawn and replaced
by new ones, saying that there was no such plan and that the
rumors are completely unfounded.
</P>
<P>
The market exchange rate between the U.S. dollar and the
Myanmar Kyat has risen sharply compared with two months ago,
trading at one U.S. dollar to more than 250 Kyats, up from one to
about 150.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
