<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rising Employment in Service Trade in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The service sector now plays an
increasingly important role in Shanghai's economic growth, with
nearly half of local employees involved in the industry, a big
rise from the 20 percent reported in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the number of employees in the city's industrial
sector accounts for 52 percent of the local total, a drop from 70
percent in 1990, when the industrial enterprises were the major
source of employment.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the positive shift of workers from manufacturing to
service jobs is a result of technological improvements and the
restructuring of industrial setups in enterprises. The change in
employment distribution in Shanghai will contribute to the
city's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai officials say they will give priority to the
development of the service trade for a long period of time, in a
bid to alleviate the existing employment problem.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the China's opening-up policies, the city has
readjusted its economic setup, with the service trade topping the
list, followed by industry and agriculture, according to local
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Output value of the service trade is expected to make up more
than two-thirds of the local GNP in the future, up from the
current 44 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0218 </DOCNO>
