<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rica to Launch Program Against Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A national program to combat
child labor in Costa Rica will be given a big push in the next
three weeks by different national institutions.
</P>
<P>
A national committee will be set up to draw up rules.
</P>
<P>
Among other measures, Costa Rica will adapt its labor law to
international norms and revise its educational system.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica's labor code sets the minimum working age at 12, as
compared to the 15-year-old norm of the international practice.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica decided to revise its educational system as experts
found that poverty is not the main reason for child labor.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that less than a fifth of the 150,000-strong
child labor force in the Central American country work because of
extreme poverty.
</P>
<P>
Experts said it is the cultural norms which oblige males to be
the bread earners of the household that has a decisive effect on
child labor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
