<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Achieve 10 percent Increase in GDP This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- China's largest industrial city
of Shanghai is trying to score a 10 percent increase in gross
domestic product (GDP) this year, the Shanghai-based Business News
quoted Mayor Xu Kuangdi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's GDP -- the value of goods and services produced --
amounted to 154.36 billion yuan during the first half of this
year, a 13.7 percent increase from the same period in 1996,
 fulfilling half of the annual target.
</P>
<P>
The city will rely primarily on the service sector to achieve
the expected GDP growth, and is taking steps to enable the sector
to contribute about 45 percent to the GDP, with priority given to
such industries as tourism, commerce, real estate, and post and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The city government will continue to improve the internal
structure of the service sector, in a bid to spur the development
of other sectors, Xu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
