<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest China City Taking on New Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Chengdu, capital of southwest
China's Sichuan Province, plays an increasingly important role in
the local development after the provincial largest city of
Chongqing became China's fourth municipality on March 14.
</P>
<P>
With a history of 2,300 years, Chengdu was one of China's first
24 cities granted by the central government the status of famous
historical and cultural city.
</P>
<P>
An important city in southwest China, Chengdu was given
approval in 1992 to become an inland open city enjoying the same
preferential policies as coastal open cities.
</P>
<P>
One year later, Chengdu was defined by the central government
as southwest China's scientific, technological, commercial, trade
and financial center and a transportation and communications hub.
</P>
<P>
Except for geographical disadvantages, the city with a
population of 9.8 million has advantages of its own. Thanks to its
booming consumer goods market, the city now ranks third among
China's 14 largest cities in terms of the open market trade volume
and the number of business people and establishments.
</P>
<P>
Located on the fertile West Sichuan Plain, Chengdu is an
important grain, oil, meat, and vegetable production base. It also
has a solid industrial foundation and a comprehensive industrial
system built up on the basis of such mainstay industries as
machinery, electronics, telecom, pharmaceuticals, chemicals and
food-stuffs.
</P>
<P>
The city has 20 higher education institutions and about 440,000
scientists and technicians.
</P>
<P>
The city's financial sector had made a breakthrough in opening
up to the outside world in recent years. Eight renowned foreign
banking institutions have opened representative offices in
Chengdu, together with a branch set up here by the Overseas
Chineses Banking Corp. of Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The city has made great effort to improve its investment
environment. This helps the city attract more than 2.4 billion US
dollars of contracted overseas funds from more than 30 countries
and regions by the end of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
