<HEADLINE> Brief Latin American Economic News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Industrial production in Colombia dropped
by 6.94 percent during the first quarter of this year compared
with the same period in 1996. Of the 29 industrial branches
registered, only five had positive growth during this period.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentine Economy Minister Roque Fernandez
visited the United States, Great Britain and France to seek
investors for the privatization of the Banco Hipotecario Nacional
(BHN or National Mortgage Bank).
</P>
<P>
The minister wanted to use BHN shares as collateral for a 2
billion-dollar loan for an ambitious social welfare program.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- A Chilean trade mission made up of experts from
Pension Fund Administrators and in private health care systems
will arrive in Nicaragua on July 24, announced the Chilean
embassy in Managua.
</P>
<P>
The group is interested in taking part in managing pension
funds and health care for short or intermediate terms in this
Central American country.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama is in the third round of negotiations
with Mexico for the signing of a free trade agreement that could
increase its market, announced Panamanian Mission Chief Yuri
Moreno.
</P>
<P>
The agreement covers trade in goods and services and investment
regulations. Panama is about to sign a free trade agreement with
Chile and with the Central American region as a bloc.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations between Panama and Mexico are still in the
beginning stages and no date has been set for the signing of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO -- Uruguay's trade with the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) climbed to 2.71 billion dollars during the 12 months
ending in March, representing an increase of 18.8 percent compared
with the year before.
</P>
<P>
Brazil accounted for the biggest share with a total of 1.61
billion dollars, 17.1 percent more than a year ago. Its trade with
Argentina rose to 1.02 billion dollars, a growth of 19.3 percent
compared with the 12 months ending March 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
