<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Troops Start to Leave East Slovenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. peacekeeping forces on Tuesday
started to leave Eastern Slovenia, an area to be reverted to
Croatia by mid-January next year.
</P>
<P>
At the headquarters of the U.N. Transitional Authority in
Eastern Slovenia (UNTAES), a farewell ceremony was held for the
2,400 departing soldiers of the Pakistani and Jordanian battalions
and an Argentine technical unit.
</P>
<P>
With the departure of these soldiers, the U.N. peacekeeping
force in the region would be downsized to 2,500, which would be
further reduced to 720 by October 15, according to Major General
Willy Hanset, commander of the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
And all U.N. troops will leave by January 15, 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Slovenia was once seized by rebelling Serbs who opposed
the independence of Croatia from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement reached at the end of 1995, it would return
to Croatia after a maximum of two years of U.N. administration.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on Monday adopted a resolution
extending the mandate of UNTAES to January 15, 1998, by which date
the administration of Eastern Slovenia would be fully assumed by
the Croatian government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the farewell ceremony, Jacques Klein from the
UNTAES said that U.N. troops had achieved a lot in the past 18
months, including demilitarizing the region and creating security
environment for local elections, thus paying the way for a
peaceful solution to one of the major problems in the Balkan
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
