<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Program Set for Ukrainian Economic Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 15 (Xinhua) -- President Leonid Kuchma published a
seven-point program on Tuesday to speed up Ukraine's
market-oriented economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The basic reason for the present economic crisis, Kuchma said,
is the lack of clear guiding lines. Various sectors of economy had
different ideas, leading to a chaos of the country's economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
The market-oriented economic reforms are the fundamental
measures to save the country from worsening economic crisis, said
Kuchma, who made similar proposals back in October 1994, but
achieved no apparent success.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Ukrainian government to tighten macro-economic
control, ignoring wide-spread complaints about over-regulation.
</P>
<P>
"It's too early and too dangerous to expect the market to
self-adjust its functions," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian economy slipped by about 10 percent in 1996 and
is still declining, though at a slower speed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Explosion Involving OSCE in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) on Tuesday reported an explosion
Monday night near the apartment of an OSCE international employee
in Banja Luka, northern Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The explosive device was detonated around 1:40 a.m. local time
(0040 GMT) outside an apartment building. It shattered the windows
of the OSCE worker's residence on the ground floor, OSCE spokesman
David Foley said. No one was hurt in the blast.
</P>
<P>
This was the second incident in two days involving the OSCE in
the Serb entity since NATO's operation to catch war crime suspects
there. But it was not clear whether the blast was targeted at the
OSCE personnel.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, an OSCE pickup was destroyed just outside its office
in Zvornik by a bomb placed beneath the car engine.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the successive occurrence of explosions involving
OSCE, Foley said that it "is troubling and causes considerable
concern." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Foreign Trade Down in First Five Months 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign trade decreased 3
percent to 59 billion U.S. dollars in the first five months of
1997, the State Statistics Commission said today.
</P>
<P>
The figures released by the commission showed that the
country's favorable trade surplus in this period reached 11
billion dollars, 2.2 billion more than the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Its imports slashed 8 percent to 24 billion dollars and its
exports rose only 0.4 percent to 35 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
