<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Inflation Keeps Interest Rate Subsidy at Zero </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China,
China's central bank, since May has set the interest rate subsidy
for long-term deposits at zero, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an official with the central bank as saying
that the move was made because the country has since 1996 kept the
inflation rate lower than the interest rate of bank deposits.
</P>
<P>
China's inflation rate was two percent in the first five months
of this year, while the interest rate for fixed one-year deposits
is 7.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate subsidy, paid on top of normal interest rates
on deposits of more than three years, was 0.17 percent in April
and 0.94 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate subsidy was introduced in China twice during
the past decade to attract long-term bank deposits during a period
of high inflation.
</P>
<P>
China stopped paying subsidies on new deposits as of April last
year because inflation has been easing. The subsidy is still paid
on long-term deposits made before April last year.
</P>
<P>
The official said the central bank would continue to calculate
the subsidy rate according to the national commodity retail and
service price index supplied by the State Statistics Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
