<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says NATO Expansion Good for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will create significant
opportunities for the U.S. to expand markets in the former Warsaw
Pact countries, the State Department said today.
</P>
<P>
Through the expansion, the U.S. underscores its role as a major
player in European security decisions, Undersecretary Stuart
Eizenstat told a press conference at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said that prospects for American business will be
enhanced in an area eager to make deals with the U.S. and the U.S.
will get economic benefit from it, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The mere fact that we are there, that we are a physical
presence _ obviously we're also a large purchasing presence in
Europe _ when you have 100,000 troops you do create a significant
economic presence, which is important," he said.
</P>
<P>
The news conference was part of a campaign by the Clinton
administration to sell the expansion of NATO to the U.S. public
and to seek the approval of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member NATO decided to accept Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic as new members at its special summit in Madrid
last week.
</P>
<P>
But many lawmakers in the U.S. opposed the expansion, arguing
that the Cold War has ended and there is no more enemy for the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said that there are "tremendous infrastructure needs"
by the new members in environmental and telecommunication areas.
"This offers fantastic opportunities."
</P>
<P>
"Obviously there are also military sales opportunities,
although we don't emphasize these," he added.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that U.S. weapons dealers have actually started
negotiations on the purchase of U.S.-made weapons by the Central
and Eastern European nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UN Members Condemn Continuous Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Overwhelming majority of
some 40 speakers at the UN General Assembly today condemned
Israel's continuous construction of settlements at Jebel Abu
Ghneim and other illegal activities in occupied Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the resumed 10th Emergency Special Session of the
General Assembly, Nasser Al-Kidwa, permanent observer for
Palestine, said that the Israeli government had resumed colonial
settlement in order to acquire more Palestinian land by force,
seize the city of Jerusalem and impose its will on the Palestinian
people. To achieve that, it was trying to exert as much pressure
as possible, including economic suffocation and a defamation
campaign against the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Palestinian people had made many
concessions with respect to their historic rights in their
homeland in order to achieve peace. The Palestinian people and
leaders were still committed to their strategic decision to engage
in the peace process and to uphold their agreements with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ibra Deguene Ka of Senegal, chairman of the Committee on the
Exercise of the Inalienable Rights of the Palestinian People, said
that Israel was implementing illegal measures to alter Jerusalem's
character, legal status and demographic composition, including
attempts to deal with Palestinian Jerusalemites as "resident
immigrants."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian Rights Committee condemned all resort to
violence, particularly against civilians, and recalled that the
peace process had made progress because both parties had agreed to
the basic principle of land for peace. He urged the international
community to stem and reverse the downward spiral in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Arab Group, Nabil A. Elaraby of Egypt
said that Secretary-General Kofi Annan's report indicated that an
avalanche of illegal measures had been taken by the Israeli
government in the occupied territories. Such activities, which
contradicted Israel's own commitments, dealt a fatal blow to
peace. Israel had imposed obstacles on the Secretary-General's
intended mission to the territories; the international community
must reject such lack of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
F.A. Shamim Ahmed of Bangladesh said that three months ago the
international community had called on Israel to cease its
construction of illegal settlement at Jebel Abu Ghneim. Sadly,
Israel had ignored that call. It had also continued its
economically crippling policies, with a view to eroding the
capacity of the Palestinian people to survive as an independent
community. The Israeli government was following a deliberate
policy of destroying the peace process, with a view to depriving
the Palestinian people of any mechanisms to pursue their goal of
establishing a Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Ali Sulaiman R. Al-Saeid of Kuwait called on the international
community to support the peace process by demanding that Israel
stop building settlements at Jebel Abu Ghneim and other occupied
areas. Israel should be asked to cease all illegal administrative
measures in Jerusalem, to accept the application of the Fourth
Geneva Protocol to the occupied territories, and to implement
Security Council resolutions 242 and 338 and other relevant
international instruments.
</P>
<P>
Hasmy Agam of Malaysia urged Israel to understand the
importance of keeping promises and honoring treaties and
agreements into which it had willingly entered. It must heed the
voice of the Assembly and respect the expressed will of the
international community. Member states with close relations to
Israel should counsel the Israeli government to act responsibly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
