<DOCNO> XIE19970716.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Calls on Halting Support for Israeli Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The UN General Assembly
today adopted a resolution requesting UN member states to halt any
support for Israeli settlements in occupied territories and ban
imports produced in the settlements.
</P>
<P>
Following a recent report of Secretary-General Kofi Annan that
Israel had not abandoned construction at Jebel Abu Ghneim, the
resumed 10th emergency special session of the General Assembly
condemned the failure of the Israeli government to comply with the
demands in resolution ES-10/2 made by the General Assembly at its
10th emergency special cession on April 25.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted with 131 votes in favor, 3 against
(Israel, Micronesia and the U.S.) and 14 abstentions, the assembly
also condemned the lack of cooperation of the Israeli government
and its attempts to impose restrictions upon mission of the
special envoy of the UN Secretary-General to Israel and the
occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Reaffirming that all illegal Israeli actions in occupied
territories remained illegal and could not be recognized
irrespective of the passage of time, the assembly reiterated the
demands made in its resolution ES-10/2, in particular the
immediate and full cessation of the construction of a new
settlement at Jebel Abu Ghneim, and of all other Israeli
settlement activities, as well as of all illegal measures and
actions in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly demanded that Israel immediately cease and
reverse all actions taken illegally under international law
against Palestinian Jerusalemites and their natural rights.
</P>
<P>
Hinting at a future attempt to suspend Israel from the
185-member General Assembly, the resolution stressed that all
member states, "in order to ensure their rights and benefits
resulting from membership, should fulfil in good faith the
obligations assumed by them in accordance with the provisions of
the Charter of the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
The assembly recommended convening of a conference by parties
to the Fourth Geneva Convention, which bars settlements in
occupied territory, to ensure respect for the convention.
</P>
<P>
The General Assembly also called for reinjecting momentum into
the stalled Middle East peace process, and for the implementation
of the agreements reached between Israeli government and the
Palestine Liberation Organization, as well as for the upholding of
the principles of the process, including the exchange of land for
peace.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of over 40 countries spoke at today's meeting.
Overwhelming majority condemned Israel's illegal activities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
