<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Asylum for Swiss Bank Guard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
representatives today approved a bill granting asylum to a Swiss
bank guard who saved precious Holocaust-era documents from a paper
shredder.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed by a voice vote. A similar legislation was
approved by the Senate in May.
</P>
<P>
Christophe Meili, 29, when working in a Swiss bank in January,
found documents dating to the Holocaust during the Second World
War. The bank had planned to destroy the documents.
</P>
<P>
Meili secretly rescued some of them and passed them to a Jewish
organization. Swiss prosecutors say Meili may have violated the
country's strict bank secrecy laws and could be jailed.
</P>
<P>
Feeling not safe in his native country of Switzerland, Meili
and his family fled to the U.S. in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
