<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Court Sentences Serb Innkeeper to 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A Bosnian Serb was sentenced
Monday in the Hague by a United Nations tribunal to 20 years in
prison for killing and torturing his Muslim and Croatian neighbors
during the Bosnian civil war.
</P>
<P>
The male innkeeper, Dusan Tadic, will serve behind the bars a
total of 97 years for 11 separate war crimes and crimes against
humanity. But the longest term was 20 years and the others were to
run concurrently.
</P>
<P>
The judge said that Tadic had beaten his victims "intentionally
and with sadistic brutality, using knives, weapons, iron bars, the
butt of a pistol, sticks and by kicking."
</P>
<P>
The defendant even once tightened a noose around the neck of a
prisoner to make the person unconscious, the judge said.
</P>
<P>
The sentence was the first handed down by an international
court after a full-length trial since the years after World War
II.
</P>
<P>
The sentence reportedly angered Bosnian Serbian leaders, who
are worried about the possibility of the international community
holding more of them accountable for what they did during the
1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serbs' president, Mrs. Biljana Plavsic, and Momcilo
Krajisnik, the Serbian member of the collective Bosnian
presidency, both criticized the verdict as unjust. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
