<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Report on Tourism in 1995-96 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)
maintained its leading position in world tourism with a growth
rate of 4.2 percent in 1996 in terms of international arrivals and
4.5 percent in terms of receipts, says a report adopted by the EU
today.
</P>
<P>
The report examines the progress made in each area of community
activity relevant to tourism and underlines the relevant
contribution of tourism-related activities to the EU economies in
terms of GDP, employment and international trade.
</P>
<P>
"The progressive impact of community actions reflects the
recognition of the potential contribution of tourism to achieving
the general objectives of the Union and the value added which
community actions bring in terms of the balanced and sustainable
development of tourism," said EU Commissioner Christos Papoutsis.
</P>
<P>
The report shows that the great majority of community programs
and policies either now include a tourism dimension or have a
significant impact on tourism-related activities.
</P>
<P>
Tourism affects directly or indirectly European citizens,
public authorities at various administrative levels, European
enterprises and tourism interests in third countries, according to
the report.
</P>
<P>
Tourism activities employ directly nine million people,
representing six percent of total employment in the EU.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that, by the end of the next decade, travel and
tourism jobs will have increased by some two million, and will
represent over nine percent of total employment in the European
Union.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
