<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Lends Totaling $19.1 Bln in Fiscal 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank today said its
new lending commitments to developing countries totaled 19.1
billion U.S. dollars in fiscal year 1997, which ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
The figure includes both the market-rate loans made by the
International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) and
the concessional loans made to the world's poorest countries
through the International Development Association (IDA).
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank's announcement, this year's lending
is lower than that of 21.4 billion dollars in fiscal 1996 and 22.5
billion dollars in fiscal 1995.
</P>
<P>
IBRD loan commitment in the year amounted to 14.5 billion
dollars, which is about three-quarters of the total, for 141
projects, 4.6 billion dollars in IDA credits supported 100
projects.
</P>
<P>
IBRD and IDA combined gross disbursements at the end of fiscal
year 1997 rose to nearly 20 billion dollars, about 4 percent up
from 19.3 billion dollars in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Among the top ten borrowers in the fiscal year, the World
Bank's commitments to China total 2,815 million U.S. dollars,
which is followed by Russia with 1,715.6 million dollars. The
third and fourth largest borrowers are India, with 1,529.5 million
dollars and Argentina, 1,479.5 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
