<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Athenians Say "No" to EURO, Schengen Treaty, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Most residents in the Greek capital
favor Greece's entry into the European Economic and Monetary Union
(EMU), but they say "no" both to the Schengen Treaty and the euro,
the common currency of the European Union (EU), according to a
poll published in today's Athens News newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by PRC from June 30 to July 7 during
which 976 people in Athens were interviewed.
</P>
<P>
The poll found that 58.4 percent of the interviewees agree with
the view that if Greece does not manage in the next three years to
join the EMU, this will have negative, perhaps even catastrophic,
consequences for the country's future.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven percent are against the Schengen Treaty, only 17.9
percent are for the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 51.1 percent say "no" to the common currency as
opposed to 33.6 percent who say "yes".
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the Greek government has taken harsh economic
measures aimed at meeting the EMU criteria as early as possible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
